# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: trousers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:trousers/a-line-clothing] An **A-line** skirt is a skirt that is fitted at the hips and gradually widens towards the hem, giving the impression of the shape of a capital letter A.
[src:trousers/a-line-clothing] The term is also used to describe dresses and coats with a similar shape.
[src:trousers/a-line-clothing] The term was first used by the French couture designer Christian Dior as the label for his collection of spring 1955.
[src:trousers/a-line-clothing] The *A-Line* collection's feature item, then the "most wanted silhouette in Paris", was a "fingertip-length flared jacket worn over a dress with a very full, pleated skirt".
[src:trousers/a-line-clothing] Although an A-shape, this silhouette was not identical to what is now understood to embody the A-line idea.
[src:trousers/a-line-clothing] That idea was given its definitive expression and popularized by Dior's successor, Yves Saint Laurent, with his "Trapeze Line" of spring 1958, which featured dresses flaring out dramatically from a fitted shoulder line.
[src:trousers/a-line-clothing] A-line clothes remained popular in the 1960s and 70s, disappeared from fashion almost completely by the early 1980s and were revived by the retro trend of the late 1990s.
[src:trousers/a-line-clothing] By that time, "A-line" was used more loosely to describe any dress wider at the hips than at the bust or waist, as well as a number of flared skirt styles.
[src:trousers/a-line-clothing] "True" A-line shapes on the pattern of Dior and Saint Laurent saw a revival in the early 2000s.
[src:trousers/a-line-clothing] The A-line skirt has no visible embellishments for ease, such as pleats or slits, but is fitted to the upper hip by means of seams and/or darts.
[src:trousers/a-line-clothing] However, denim A-line skirts often have buttons down the center seam.
[src:trousers/a-line-clothing] Its fastening is usually kept discreet, with a side or back zipper.
[src:trousers/a-line-clothing] Pockets may be present, but not usually.
[src:trousers/a-line-clothing] When referring to dresses and coats, the term *A-line* generally means fitted from the shoulders to the hips and then widening to the hem, but it is also sometimes used to mean widening from the shoulders to the hem, ignoring the waist and hips.
[src:trousers/a-line-clothing] It is often used to describe a popular style of wedding dress, which is fitted above and around the hips but flares gently to the hem, giving a streamlined and quite slim look.
[src:trousers/abolla] An ***abolla*** was a cloak-like garment worn by ancient Greeks and Romans.
[src:trousers/abolla] Nonius Marcellus quotes a passage of Varro to show that it was a garment worn by soldiers (*vestis militaris*), and thus opposed to the toga.
[src:trousers/abolla] Roman women also wore a version of the *abolla* by at least the imperial period.
[src:trousers/abolla] The *abolla* was, however, not confined to military occasions, but was also worn in the city.
[src:trousers/abolla] It was especially used by the Stoic and Cynic philosophers at Rome as the *pallium philosophicum*, just as the Greek philosophers were accustomed to distinguish themselves by a particular dress.
[src:trousers/abolla] Hence, the expression of Juvenal *facinus majoris abollae* merely signifies, "a crime committed by a very deep philosopher".
[src:trousers/abolla] Ptolemy of Mauretania wore a purple cloak so luxurious that it is theorized that Caligula had him executed out of jealousy.
[src:trousers/abolla] The term *abolla* is actually a Latinization of the Greek *ambolla* (ἀμβόλλα) or *anabole* (ἀναβολή), for a loose woolen cloak.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] Contemporarily, it is commonly seen only at graduation ceremonies, but formerly academic dress was, and to a lesser degree in many ancient universities still is, worn daily.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] Today, the ensembles are distinctive in some way to each institution, and generally consist of a gown (also known as a robe) with a separate hood, and usually a cap (generally a square academic cap, a tam, or a bonnet).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] Academic dress is also worn by members of certain learned societies and institutions as official dress.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] The academic dress found in most universities in the Commonwealth of Nations and the United States is derived from that of the universities of Oxford and Cambridge, which was a development of academic and clerical dress common throughout the medieval universities of Europe.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] This overgarment had the practical purpose of keeping a scholar warm while they were sitting, immobile, or studying.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] Formal or sober clothing is typically worn beneath the gown: for example, men would often wear a dark suit with a white shirt and a tie, or clerical clothing, military or civil uniform, or national dress, and women would wear equivalent attire.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] Some older universities, particularly Oxford and Cambridge, have a prescribed set of dress (known as *subfusc*) to be worn under the gown, though this sometimes refers only to requiring the proper wear of academic dress and not what is worn beneath it, if unseen.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] In the Commonwealth, gowns are worn open, while in the United States, with a few exceptions, it has become common for gowns to close at the front, as did the original *roba*.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] In general, the materials used for academic dress are heavily influenced by the climate where the academic institution is located, or the climate where the graduate will usually be wearing the costume (as a faculty member at another institution, for example).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] In either case, the American Council of Education (ACE) allows for the comfort of the wearer, and concedes that lighter materials be used in tropical climates, and heavier materials elsewhere.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] In addition, it acknowledges cotton poplin, broadcloth, rayon, or silk as appropriate.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] The materials used for academic dress vary and range from the extremely economical to the very expensive.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] In the United States, most bachelor's and master's degree candidates are often presented the "souvenir" version of regalia by their institutions or authorized vendor, which are generally intended for very few wearings and are comparatively very inexpensive.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] For some doctoral graduates, commencement will be the only time they wear academic regalia, and so they rent their gowns instead of buying them.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] These rented or hired gowns are often made of inexpensive polyester or other human-made synthetic fibre.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] In Britain, rented gowns are almost always polyester while Russell cord, silk, or artificial silk gowns are only available when bought.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] Undergraduate gowns are usually made from cotton or cotton and polyester mix and are relatively inexpensive to encourage students to own them.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] People who choose to buy their dress may opt for finer fabrics, such as poplin, grosgrain, percale, cotton, wool, cassimere, broadcloth, Russell cord, or corded/ribbed material.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] For silk, there are a range of types including artificial silk/rayon, Ottoman (i.e. ribbed or corded silk), taffeta, satin, alpaca, true silk, shot silk, or a mixture.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] Pure Ottoman silk is rarely used except for official gowns, as it is very expensive.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] Some gowns may be trimmed with gimp lace, cords, buttons, or other forms of decoration.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] In the past, fur has been used to line certain hoods (especially those of the UK) which range from rabbit to ermine.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] Most now use imitation fur, instead, mainly because of cost and animal rights concerns.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] Some robe makers use fur if the customer requests and pays for it, as some feel that the quality and feel of artificial fur has yet to match that of real fur.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] Doctors' robes usually use wool flannel, panama wool (worsted), superfine cloth, damask, or brocade, and are brightly coloured (or black, but faced with a bright colour) to distinguish them from lower degrees.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] They tend to be the most expensive because they must be dyed in a specific colour and/or be trimmed in coloured silks.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] Many doctoral gowns have a special undress version, so adding to the cost of a full set.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p01] As such, suppliers of academic dress produce gowns in many different sizes to fit persons of different heights.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Academic regalia typically consist of a headgear (mortarboard, Tudor bonnet, or John Knox cap), robe, and hood.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Until the 1930s, Canadian universities customarily prescribed academic robes for its professors and students at classes and lectures.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] At the University of Trinity College in the University of Toronto, academic gowns are still required for all students and faculty at Wednesday dinners, most college meetings, debates, and certain special college events.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Most Canadian universities follow or adopted either the British University academic dress at Oxford or Cambridge universities, or the Intercollegiate Code of Academic Costume ratified by most American universities in the late 1890s.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Other universities contain elements of the British and American patterns for some or all of their academic costumes.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] A classic example is the academic dress of McGill University, whose British origins are evident in the regalia of its degree holders.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The distinctive ceremonial regalia of McGill University officials, though, are closer to the American pattern for the master's robe with above-the-elbow, square, slit-cut sleeves.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The scarlet, doctor of philosophy (PhD) regalia of McGill can now be worn closed-front, unlike the open-front only gown of the University of Cambridge higher doctoral full dress, from which it evolved.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Gold strand tassels used in American doctoral regalia are wrapped around McGill's otherwise Tudor-style bonnet or tam.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] In France, academic dress, also called the *toge* (from the word *toga*, an ancient Roman garment), is similar to French judges' court dress, except for its colour, which depends on the academic field in which the wearer graduated.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] It is nowadays little worn, except by doctors during the opening of the university year or the ceremony for a doctorate *honoris causa*.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Professors who served 20 years are sometimes presented with a sword (identical model to that of French police commissars).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The colours of the various academic fields are daffodil (yellow) for literature and arts, amaranth (purplish red) for science, redcurrant (reddish pink) for medicine, scarlet red for law, and violet (purple) for theology.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] University rectors, chancellors or presidents wear also specific costumes, which are violet regardless of the academic field in which they graduated.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The dress exists in two versions: the *petit costume* ("small costume") and the *grand costume* ("great costume").
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] In formal occasions, the *grand costume* is equivalent to white tie, whereas the *petit costume* is equivalent to black tie.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] German academic dress generally consists of gown and cap.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Nowadays, if in use at all, it is only found at special occasions, such as public processions, inaugurations of rectors, and graduation ceremonies.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Historically, only the rectors, deans, professors, and lecturers wore academic dress—not students or graduates.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Each German university had its own system of colours and drapings to signify faculty membership and position in the university hierarchy.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The gown of the German academic dress is called "Talar" (with the accent on the second "a": talár; from Latin *talare* which means *to the ankles*).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] It can be traced back to the everyday clothes of the scholars in the Middle Ages.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The professorial *Talar* can be described as a long black gown with wide sleeves, often with lapels in faculty colour, while deans wear a *Talar* completely in faculty colour.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Rectors typically have a distinguished, more elaborate *Talar*, e.g., made of velvet, coloured in red, or with gold embroidery.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] At some universities, the rector additionally wears a chain of office and, at some occasions, carries a scepter.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The cap that accompanies the *Talar* is called *Barett*.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] As is the case with the *Talar*, which type of cap is used varies by university as well.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Historically, caps made of soft materials rather than the square academic cap are common.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The colour of the *Barett* matches the *Talar*.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] In East Germany, which was a communist one-party state, *Talare* were abolished by law at about the same time.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] After East Germany began to dissolve in 1989, several universities, particularly University of Rostock, University of Greifswald, University of Jena, and University of Halle-Wittenberg, resurrected lost traditions including the *Talar* for officials.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Some traditional universities in West German states have since followed, such as University of Heidelberg.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Since 2005, some universities introduced centrally organized graduation ceremonies for students of all faculties where academic dress is worn, most notably University of Bonn, Chemnitz University of Technology, and RWTH Aachen (only cap and stole).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The graduates' dress usually consists of a simple black gown, a square academic cap, and possibly a stole in faculty colour.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] At most other universities, faculties are responsible for organizing graduation ceremonies individually.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Some faculties have decided for wearing academic dress at their ceremonies as well, e.g., the Faculty of Law at University of Marburg and the Faculty of Economics and Business Administration at Goethe University Frankfurt.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] This practice is commonly understood as following Anglo-American examples rather than reviving old traditions.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Indian universities followed United Kingdom robe and gown system until 2013 when Banaras Hindu University replaced it with Indian traditional dress of Kurta, Dhoti, Pyajama for men and Saree for women, which led to students at other universities demanding similar dresses.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Slowly Indian universities started replacing the robes and gowns with traditional dresses.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] In 2019, India's University Grants Commission formally issued a circular to all public and private universities to opt for Indian traditional dress made of Indian handloom.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Indian universities today prescribe Kurta, Pyajama for male students and Saree or Salwar Suit for women.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] In Indonesia, academic regalia, also called a *toga* is only worn in graduation ceremonies.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] An Indonesian toga generally comes in three pieces of clothing: a gown, a cape or a hood, and a cap with tassel (pentagon-shaped mortarboard/bonnet).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Other items are also worn during graduation ceremony such as a medallion, tippet or academic stole.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Usually gowns are worn only by professors during ceremonies and, in some faculties, during graduations.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] After the student protests of 1968 many professors in many universities had stopped wearing academical gowns also in the formal occasions but since the 1990s people have started to use them again, mostly in humanities faculties.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Furthermore, also students have started to wear gowns and cap in graduation ceremonies (usually for PhD) in some universities.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Gowns are traditionally all hemmed with the colours of faculty, which have some variations following the tradition of each atheneum.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] In Malaysia, most public university academic gowns incorporate Songket motifs, apart from being influenced by the academic dress system in the United Kingdom which incorporates Tudor bonnets for doctorates and mortarboard for master's and bachelor's degree holders.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Some university chancellors who were royal heads of state usually incorporates yellow-colour academic gown to denote their royal status.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Certain universities, especially Universiti Teknologi MARA, Universiti Utara Malaysia, National Defence University of Malaysia and Universiti Malaysia Kelantan includes an academic sash as academic regalia specifically for first class bachelor's degree holders.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] However, academic dresses are rarely worn and usually worn during convocation ceremonies, professorship lectures. and inanugration ceremonies.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The colours denoting faculties vary according to each institution and do not have a uniformed colour code.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] At Dutch universities, academic dress does not come with a degree but with the incumbency of a professorial chair: only full, chaired professors wear the *toga* with bib and beret.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Recently established universities may show a greater variety of colours.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Academic dress is only worn on ceremonial occasions: the university anniversary or *dies natalis*, inaugural lectures, and the public defence of a doctoral thesis.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] On such occasions, the assembled professors line up as a *cortège* headed by the university beadle, who also wears an academic gown and carries the university's mace.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Male professors remove their beret when sitting down and put it on when standing up (e.g. to lecture or to address a doctoral candidate during the thesis defence).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Female professors may keep the beret on at all times.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Academic dress may be completed by a chain of office (for the presiding Rector or Dean) or the insignia of honorary doctorates or royal orders (only worn at the *dies natalis*).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] University graduates in New Zealand wear an academic gown identical to those of the University of Cambridge and either a hood or scarf, depending on whether the graduate is receiving a degree or diploma.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] If the graduate is receiving a degree, a hood will be worn throughout the ceremony.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] If a diploma is received, the graduate will wear a diploma scarf.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The hood, like the gown, is identical to that of the hood for the Cambridge Master of Arts.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] A bachelor's degree hood is lined with coloured satin and bordered with white fur (the exception to this are Canterbury and Waikato University which do not line their hoods with fur).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The bachelor's degree with honours hood is lined with coloured satin and bordered with white satin.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] A doctoral degree recipient wears the same as a graduate receiving a master's degree, except the gown is completely silk, either black or scarlet, with the option to wear a cloth gown.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] A Doctoral hood is completely silk and the headdress is a black Tudor bonnet, in place of the flat-topped mortarboard worn with bachelor's and master's gowns.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Academic dress is rarely worn in New Zealand other than at formal academic events, such as by graduates and faculty at graduation ceremonies and teaching faculty at school prizegivings.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Some traditional boys' high schools retain the tradition of the headmaster wearing a gown while leading assemblies.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Undergraduates who live at College House at the University of Canterbury must wear academic dress to dinner.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] It is common for graduands to wear clothing or adornments significant to their culture at their graduation ceremony.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] For example, it is common to see Māori students wearing a traditional cloak known as *korowai* or *kakahu huruhuru* or Pasifika students wearing lavalava, ta'ovala and elaborate lei.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Most colleges and universities in the Philippines follow the traditional mortarboard, hood and gown (also known as toga) during graduation.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] In some schools of the country, the color of the gown corresponds to the school color (Blue for Colegio de San Juan de Letran and Ateneo de Manila University, Green for Far Eastern University, and Red for San Beda University).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Some schools, like the University of Santo Tomas, due to their Spanish heritage, follow Spanish academic attire such as the academic biretta and mozetta.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The biretta and mozetta are worn by those from the Graduate School and the Faculty of Medicine and Surgery.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Graduates of the bachelor's programs wear the traditional mortarboard, hood and gown.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The professors of the university wear their academic regalia during the Missa de Apertura or the Opening Mass of the Academic Year aside from Solemn Investitures (graduation ceremonies) and other academic activities.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The academic colors are unique to this university as these depend on the official color of the faculty or college a student or an academe belongs into.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] A unique graduation garb worn at member universities of the University of the Philippines System is the *Sablay*, which originated from the Scandinavian academic regalia in the 1700s when the king of Sweden introduced it as a red sash worn in the same manner as the *Sablay*.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The design of the University of the Philippines System *Sablay* was inspired by the Malong of Muslim Mindanao, giving it a Filipiniana look.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] It features the indigenous baybayin characters for "U" and "P".
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The garb was first worn at the University of the Philippines Diliman.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Elementary and high school students also wear a certain kind of academic dress upon their graduation, usually a white gown and mortarboard for public schools.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] For private schools, the gown and mortarboard's color is at the discretion of the administration.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] There are several schools which make use of a hood-like design on top of their gowns which bears the school colors.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] Academic dress varies from university to university.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] In some situations, such as in doctoral exams, the hat is not used.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] In Portugal, following an ancient tradition, university regular students also use a specific dressing.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] The "traje académico", as it is known in Portuguese, is recognized by its almost totally black color and cape.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p02] But other student dresses did exist, including the unique blue attire of the students of the University of Algarve (UAlg) in use until at least to the 2010s.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Academic dress in South Africa varies from one institution to another, but generally follow UK patterns.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] A common distinction is for graduands in all degrees up to and including the master's degree to have black gowns, while the PhD candidate wears a scarlet gown.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] These days, academic dress is only used at graduation ceremonies.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The wearing of traditional African attire, or modern clothes inspired by traditional attire, beneath the academic dress has been a distinct trend in recent years.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The typical Spanish academic dress has Latin origin.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] It has been regulated since 1850, when Queen Isabella II established several rules about academic dress, according to the centuries-old Spanish custom.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] However, this academic dress is only used for the opening of the academic year and for PhD graduations or for doctorates *honoris causa*.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] It is worn only by doctors, deans and the University Rector.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] For other graduates, the academic dress is often composed by a mortarboard and a mozzetta (*muceta*) or a sash over the shoulder (*beca*) with the shield of the university and/or faculty.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The colour of the mozzetta or the sash depends on the academic field.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In Sri Lanka, the academic dress consists of gown, hood (post-graduate) and a garland (on graduation day).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Universities that were affiliated to the former University of Ceylon issue black gowns for graduates and post graduates; red gowns for master's and PhD graduates; crimson gowns for chancellors with a different colour gowns for senior academic faculty.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] These universities only issue garland on the graduation day to new graduates and only issue mortar boards to chancellor, vice chancellor and registrars.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Private universities issue mortar boards to graduates along with a hood in place of garland.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Finland and Sweden have similar traditions when it comes to academic clothing.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] For important academic ceremonies white tie is usually worn, however, often with traditional headwear and gowns.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Gowns are not generally used except by the rector as a symbol of office, if anyone.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The regular student cap (Finnish: *ylioppilaslakki*, Swedish: *studentmössa*) usually has a white velvet crown, a black band and a black beak.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The cap can be worn by anyone who has passed the matriculation examination and is acceptable wear for both formal and informal academic celebrations.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Technology students wear a special kind of student cap called a *teekkarilakki* (Finnish) or *teknologmössa* (Swedish).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] It is similar to the traditional student cap, but features a tuft and a distinctive cockade to show which university the wearer is attending.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Technology students generally wear their caps more frequently, and thus the tuft often symbolizes university engineering students.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Although universities have different rules regarding the use of the cap, caps are generally not awarded to students until the completion of the first year of studies.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The technology student's hat may also be seen on informal occasions, being worn with the student overall at many universities.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In both countries many universities have doctoral hats for persons who have completed a PhD or similar degree.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] These usually resemble top hats and must be worn with white tie.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Like other hats, they are not generally worn indoors, but they may be presented on a table.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Events where the hat and white tie are worn include thesis defences, postdoctoral parties, ceremonial conferments of degrees, opening ceremonies and other formal ceremonies related to the university.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] At some universities, a doctoral ring is awarded together with the hat.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In the Ingmar Bergman film *Wild Strawberries*, one scene shows the conferral of a Jubilee doctor degree on the main character at the University of Lund, which includes the presentation of such a hat and ring.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] At the University of Helsinki a cape and a sword are commonly worn with the doctoral hat.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Students of the student organization "Limes" may also be seen wearing a black cape.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Academic dress varies from university to university in Taiwan, generally consisting of cap and gown.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Its use is limited to such special occasions as graduation ceremonies.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In Thailand, there are five different styles of academic dress: (1) traditional Thai, (2) traditional American, (3) French (Paris), (4) modified American, and (5) modified British.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Some universities prefer a traditional robe originated in the royal court, known as suea khrui.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Traditionally, the robe is a one-piece open-fronted garment made with a mesh, faced and bordered with a velvet or felt band.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Since the conception of Chulalongkorn University, the traditional suea khrui was adopted for their graduates.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Influenced by the colour of gowns used at Oxford, bachelor's and master's gown are faced and bordered with a black felt band.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Meanwhile, a scarlet felt band is reserved for doctors.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] There are patterns upon the felt band to denote different degrees and faculties.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Other universities that utilise the traditional robe might, instead of a mesh, use another kind of fabric for their dress.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] As a note, Mahachulalongkorn and Mahamakut Buddhist universities do not prescribe an academic dress for monks, nuns and clergymen.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] It is also customary that monks and ministers of religion do not wear a dress, when they are being admitted to the degree at other Thai universities.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Other universities employs academic dress of the modified American pattern, with the exception at Thammasat University and Kasetsart University.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Thammasat University employs a plain black gown with different epitoge, a strip of cloth worn over the left shoulder, for distinct degrees.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The number of fur bands upon the epitoge indicates the degree (i.e.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] 3 for doctorate, 2 for master's and 1 for bachelor's).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Kasetsart University, on the other hand, retains the original American academic dress style.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] For bachelor's, the dress comprises a plain sleeve gown with a coloured cord around the neck.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] This is different from many American universities, at which a scarf is used instead of a cord.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Master's gown exactly follows the American design.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The sleeve is sewn shut at the end, with a slit to free the arm.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Doctors' gown also follows the American tradition.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The sleeve has three velvet bars to denote the seniority.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Since most Thai universities do not fully understand the original American tradition, they usually use an American doctoral gown for their doctoral degree.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] By reducing the number of velvet bars on the sleeve, it is possible to get gowns for master's (2 bars) and bachelor's (1 bar or none).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Notable examples of this deviation include Ramkhamhaeng University, Burapha University, Mahidol University and the University of Phayao.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Some universities even incorporate the hood into a pattern on the gown, including Suranaree University of Technology and Walailak University.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] This eliminates the need of additional hood.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Prince of Songkhla University uses a gown which is heavily deviated from the original British style.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Gowns for bachelor's and master's are made of black stuff.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Doctoral gowns are made from scarlet cloth.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Instead of being open-fronted like ones in the United Kingdom and Australia, all gowns are close-fronted, probably due to the robemakers.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The neckband is curved instead of being a chevron.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Silpakorn University mixes a modified American gown (i.e. a close-fronted black gown with different number of bars on the sleeve) with an altered version of Oxford simple hood.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In Tunisia, University of Ez-Zitouna graduates wear an academic gown.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Doctoral graduates in Islamic Sciences wear a jebba.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In other Tunisian universities, like the medical university, doctoral graduates wear an academic dress.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Academic regalia in Turkey has many similarities with the academic dress traditions of the United States.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] There is a distinction between different types of academical dress.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Most recently, gowns, hoods and caps are categorised into their shapes and patterns by the Groves classification system, which is based on Nicholas Groves' document, *Hood and Gown Patterns*.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] This lists the various styles or patterns of academic dress and assigns them a code or a Groves Classification Number.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] For example, the Cambridge BA style gown is designated [b2] and a hood in the Cambridge full-shape is designated [f1], etc.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Because the universities are free to design their own academicals using a wide range of available gown, hood and cap patterns, colours and materials at their and the robemaker's disposal, the academicals of two given universities rarely clash with each other.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The Burgon Society was founded in 2000 to promote the study of academic dress.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Its publications and activities examine the history and current use of academic dress.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In 2011 it published the third edition of Shaw's reference book on British and Irish academical dress.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The society hosts a conference each spring at which recent research is presented.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The modern gown is derived from the *roba* worn under the *cappa clausa*, a garment resembling a long black cape.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In early medieval times, all students at the universities were in at least minor orders, and were required to wear the *cappa* or other clerical dress, and restricted to clothes of black or other dark colour.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The gowns most commonly worn, that of the clerical type gowns of bachelor's degrees (BA and BS) and master's degrees (MA and MS), are substantially the same throughout the English-speaking world.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] All are traditionally made of black cloth, (although occasionally the gown is dyed in one of the university's colours) and the material at the back of the gown is gathered into a yoke.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The bachelor's gown has bell-shaped sleeves, while the master's gown has long sleeves closed at the end, with the arm passing through a slit above the elbow.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] There are two distinctive shapes used in the UK for doctors' gowns; the Oxford doctor's shape and the Cambridge doctor's shape.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The former has bell-shaped sleeves, the latter has long open sleeves.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Another rarer form is the Cambridge Doctor of Music dress gown which is a pattern between the two.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The other form of doctor's gown is the undress gown.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] This is a black gown worn for less formal occasions such as lectures.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] This type of gown is rarely seen or worn nowadays as many wear the dress gown instead; however, the undress gown still plays a part in the older universities where academic dress is usually worn.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Undergraduates at many older universities also wear gowns; the most common essentially a smaller knee-length version of the bachelor's gown, or the Oxford Commoners gown which is a sleeveless lay type gown and has two streamers at the back at Oxford.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] At Cambridge, most colleges have their own distinctive design of gown.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Undergraduates at St Andrews, with the exception of theology students, commonly wear scarlet woollen gowns with velvet collars.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Undergraduate gowns are seldom worn (even in institutions that prescribe them) nowadays except in the older universities.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Another form of dress, now rarely seen, is the habit, which is worn over a black gown.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Only Oxford, Cambridge, Durham and Newcastle use habits and mainly reserve their use for very formal ceremonial occasions and to a specific group of academics or officials.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The hood was originally a functional garment, worn to shield the head from the elements.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In the English tradition, it has developed to an often bright and decorative garment worn only on special occasions.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Hoods comprise two basic patterns: full shape or simple shape.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The traditional full-shape hood consists of a cape, cowl, and liripipe, as is used at Cambridge.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] At Oxford, the bachelor's and master's hoods use simple hoods that have lost their cape and retain only the cowl and liripipe.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The colour and lining of hoods in academic dress represent the rank and/or faculty of the wearer.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In many Commonwealth universities, bachelor's hoods are worn with edges or linings of white rabbit fur, while master's hoods are lined with coloured silk (originally ermine or other expensive fur).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Doctoral hoods are normally made of scarlet cloth and lined with coloured silk.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Faculty colours were introduced by the University of London and many universities followed suit.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The academic cap or square, commonly known as the mortarboard, has come to be symbolic of academia.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In some universities it can be worn by graduates and undergraduates alike.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] It is a hat consisting of a skullcap surmounted by a flat square of stiffened cloth, the board; a tassel is fixed to a button in the centre of the board.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The mortarboard may also be referred to as a trencher cap (or simply trencher).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The tassel is composed of a cluster of silk threads which are wrapped together with a cord which is attached to the button affixed to the centre of the headpiece.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The loose strands are allowed to fall freely over the board edge, typically falling over the left front side of the cap.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Often the strands are plaited together to form a cord with the end threads left untied.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In many universities, holders of doctorates wear a soft-crowned, round-brimmed headpiece known as a Tudor bonnet or tam, rather than a trencher.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Other types of hats used, especially in some universities in the UK, are the John Knox cap (mostly at Scottish universities), the Bishop Andrewes cap (a reinvention of the ancient form of the mortarboard, worn by Cambridge Doctors of Divinity DD's) and the pileus (at Sussex).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In some universities, such as Oxford, women may wear an Oxford ladies' cap.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Officers of the universities generally wear distinctive and more elaborate dress.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The chancellor and the vice-chancellor may wear a black damask lay type gown (sometimes with a long train) trimmed with gold or silver lace and frogs.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] They wear a velvet mortarboard, similarly trimmed with gold braid and tassel.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Other than this gown, they may have other distinct forms of dress, such as the scarlet *cappa clausa* or cope worn in certain circumstances by the vice-chancellor of Cambridge or his/her deputy and by higher doctors presenting candidates for degrees, which was once worn by Doctors of Divinity.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In the past, chancellors may also wear full court dress with breeches and court shoes like that of the lord chancellor of Great Britain.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] At degree ceremonies, graduands often dress in the academic dress of the degree to which they are about to be admitted prior to the actual graduation ceremony.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] This is not the case at several of the older universities in the UK, most notably, Oxford, Cambridge and St Andrews, which have their own distinct traditions.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In addition to universities and colleges, a number of British professional bodies, such as the Institute of Biology and the Institute of Physics grant academic dress to their members.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Academic regalia in the United States has been influenced by the academic dress traditions of Europe.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] There is an Inter-Collegiate code which sets out a detailed uniform scheme of academic regalia followed by most, though some institutions do not adhere to it entirely, and fewer still ignore it.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Generally, academic regalia in the United States consists of a mortarboard cap affixed with a tassel, and gown worn over other clothing.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The ensemble can also be adorned with an academic stole—a vestment used by various organizations to denote academic achievement.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The practice of wearing academic regalia in the United States dates to the Colonial Colleges period, and was heavily influenced by European practices and styles.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Students of most colonial colleges were required to wear the "college habit" at most times – a practice that lasted until the eve of the American Civil War in many institutions of higher learning.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In some rare instances the practice has persisted, such as at Sewanee, where members of the student honor society, along with most professors, continue to wear the gown to class.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] After the Civil War, academic regalia was generally only worn at ceremonies or when representing the institution.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] There was not, however, any standardization among the meanings behind the various costumes.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In 1893, an Intercollegiate Commission made up of representatives from leading institutions and chaired by President of Columbia Seth Low was created, to establish an acceptable system of academic dress.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The commission met at Columbia University in 1895 and adopted a code of academic regalia, which prescribed the cut and style and materials of the gowns, as well as determined the colors which were to represent the different fields of learning.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] These rules were soon adopted by Columbia's peer institutions, including Harvard, Yale, and Princeton.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The committee reviewed the situation and approved a code for academic costumes that has been in effect since that year.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] A *Committee on Academic Costumes and Ceremonies*, appointed by the American Council on Education in 1959, again reviewed the academic dress code and made several changes.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Although academic dress is now rarely worn outside commencement ceremonies or other academic rituals such as encaenia in the U.S., graduation ceremonies have gained popularity and have expanded from high school graduations to middle school, elementary school and kindergarten graduation ceremonies.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Bachelor's and master's gowns in the United States are similar to their counterparts in the United Kingdom, though bachelor's gowns are now designed to be worn closed, and all are at least mid-calf length to ankle-length.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The master's gown sleeve is oblong and, though the base of the sleeve hangs down in the typical manner, it is square cut at the rear part of the oblong shape.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The front part has an arc cut away, and there is a slit for the wrist opening, but the rest of the arc is closed.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The shape is evocative of the square-cut liripipe incorporated into many academic hoods (*see*, below).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The master's gown is designed to be worn open or closed.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Doctoral robes are typically black, although some schools use robes in the school's colours.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The Code calls for the outside shell of the hood (*see*, below) to remain black in that case, however.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In general, doctoral gowns are similar to the gowns worn by bachelor's graduates, with the addition of three velvet bands on the sleeves and velvet facing running down the front of the gown.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The Code calls for the gown trim to be either black or the colour designated for the field of study in which the doctorate was earned (see *Inter-Collegiate colors*).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] However, in the case of the degree of Doctor of Philosophy (PhD), although it is awarded for study in any number of fields, the dark blue velvet of philosophy is always used regardless of the particular field studied.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] For example, if not choosing black trim, a PhD in theology would wear velvet gown trim in dark blue, while a Doctor of Theology (Th.D.) would wear scarlet trim, if not choosing black.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The robes have full sleeves, instead of the bell sleeves of the bachelor's gown.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Some gowns expose a necktie or cravat when closed, while others take an almost cape-like form.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] It is designed to be worn open or closed in the front.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The Code calls for the shell material of the hood to match the robe, and for the colour to be black regardless of the colour of the robe being worn.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The interior lining—generally silk—displays the colours of the institution from which the wearer received the degree, in a pattern prescribed by it (usually, if more than one colour is used, chevrons or equal divisions).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The opening of the hood is trimmed in velvet or velveteen.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] In most American colleges and universities, the colour of the velvet hood trimming is distinctive of the academic field—or as closely related as possible—to which the degree earned pertains (see *Inter-Collegiate colors*).
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Many institutions, particularly larger ones, have dispensed with the bachelor's hood at commencement ceremonies altogether, though a graduate is still entitled to wear one once the degree is conferred.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Headwear is an important component of cap-and-gown, and the academic costume is not complete without it.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The headwear will vary with the level of academic achievement and, to some extent, on the individual academic institution's specifications.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] For caps, the mortarboard is recommended in the Code, and the material required to match the gown.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The exception—velvet—is reserved for the doctor's degree only, seen in the form of a multiple-sided (4, 6, or 8) tam, but the four-sided mortarboard-shaped tam in velvet is what the Code seems to recommend here.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The only colour called for is black, in all cases.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The tassel worn on the mortarboard or a tam seems to provide, by tradition, the greatest opportunity for latitude in American academic dress.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] It has been black, or represented the university's colours, or the colours of the specific college, or the discipline.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The tassel has also been used to indicate membership in national honour societies or other awards.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] There is at some colleges and universities a practice of moving the tassel from one side to the other on graduating, but this is a modern innovation that would be impractical out of doors due to the vagaries of the wind.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] For doctoral and master's students, the tassel commonly begins and remains on the left.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] A distinction is made in the code, which calls for a graduate to display the colour of the subject of the degree obtained, not the degree itself.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] For example, if a graduate is awarded a Bachelor of Arts (BA) degree specifically in business the trimming should be drab, representing commerce/accountancy/business, rather than white, representing the broader arts/letters/humanities; the same method is true of master's degrees and doctorates.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] A number of other items such as cords, stoles, aiguillettes, etc. representing various academic achievements or other honours are also worn at the discretion of some degree-granting institutions.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Technically, however, the ACE code does not allow their use on or over academic regalia.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Academic dress for pontifical universities tends to vary by the host country.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] There is no equivalent canon in the current Code of Canon Law promulgated in 1983, but the tradition remains.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Three-horned birettas are to be used by Licentiates, four-horned for Doctors.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Academic dress for the Pontifical University of Saint Thomas Aquinas, *Angelicum* graduates consists of a black toga or academic gown with trim to follow the color of the faculty, and an academic ring.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] For the doctoral degree a four corned biretta is to be worn, and for the Licentiate degree a three corned biretta is to be worn.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] See: Academic regalia of the Pontifical University of St.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] The 'traditional' biretta at the Pontifical University of Saint Thomas Aquinas, *Angelicum*, is white, to correspond to the white Dominican habit.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] Also, the academic senate of the *Angelicum* in its May 2011 meeting indicated that the black biretta may be used with trim and pom in the color of the particular faculty.
[src:trousers/academic-dress-p03] A three-peaked black biretta with appropriately colored piping may be similarly used by those receiving the licentiate degree (S.T.L., Ph.L.).
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] African-American history began in the 16th century, when mainly West African and Central African slave traders sold African artisans, farmers, and warriors to European slave traders, who transported them across the Atlantic to the Western Hemisphere.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] They were sold as slaves to European colonists and put to work on plantations, particularly in the southern colonies.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] A few were able to achieve freedom through manumission or escape, and founded independent communities before and during the American Revolution.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] After the United States was founded in 1783, most American Black people continued to be enslaved, primarily in the American South, with four million enslaved people only liberated after the Northern victory over the South in the Civil War of 1861 to 1865.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] During Reconstruction, African Americans gained citizenship and adult-males the right to vote; however, due to widespread belief in White supremacy, they were treated as second-class citizens and soon effectively disenfranchised in the South.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] These circumstances changed due to participation in the military conflicts of the United States, substantial migration out of the South, the elimination of legal racial segregation, and the civil rights movement which sought political and social freedom.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] However, racism against African Americans and racial socioeconomic disparity remain a problem into the 21st century.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In the 20th and 21st centuries, immigration has played an increasingly significant role in the African-American community.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Black population were immigrants, and 20% were either immigrants or the children of immigrants.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] While some Black immigrants or their children may also come to identify as African American, the majority of first-generation immigrants do not, preferring to identify with their nation of origin.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Most African Americans are of West African and coastal Central African ancestry, with varying amounts of Western European and Native American ancestry (see §Genetics).
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] African-American culture has had a significant influence on worldwide culture, making numerous contributions to the English language, literature, politics, cuisine, sports, and music.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The African-American contribution to popular music is so profound that most American popular music, including gospel, blues, jazz, rock and roll, R&B, soul, funk, disco, hip-hop, and house has its origins either partially or entirely in the African-American community.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The vast majority of those who were enslaved and transported in the transatlantic slave trade were people from several Central and West African ethnic groups.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] They had been captured directly by European slave traders in coastal raids, or captured and sold by West African slave traders or by half-European "merchant princes" to European slave traders, who brought them to the Americas.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The first African slaves in what is now the United States arrived in the early 16th century.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Africans were among Juan Ponce de León's 1513 voyage that landed in what would become Spanish Florida, and enslaved Africans arrived around the same time to Spanish Puerto Rico.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Africans also came via Santo Domingo in the Caribbean to the San Miguel de Gualdape colony (most likely located in the Winyah Bay area of present-day South Carolina), founded by Spanish explorer Lucas Vázquez de Ayllón in 1526.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The ill-fated colony was almost immediately disrupted by a fight over leadership, during which the slaves revolted and fled the colony to seek refuge among local Native Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] De Ayllón and many of the colonists died shortly afterward, due to an epidemic and the colony was abandoned.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The settlers and the slaves who had not escaped returned to the Island of Hispaniola, whence they had come.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The enslaved explorer Esteban arrived in Florida with the Narváez expedition in 1528, a journey that first landed in Santo Domingo and later traveled into Spanish Texas and the Southwest before ending in Mexico.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The marriage between Luisa de Abrego, a free Black domestic servant from Seville, and Miguel Rodríguez, a White Segovian conquistador in 1565 in St.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Augustine (Spanish Florida), is the first known and recorded Christian marriage anywhere in what is now the continental United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The first recorded Africans in English America (including most of the future United States) were "20 and odd negroes" who arrived in Jamestown, Virginia via Cape Comfort in August 1619 as indentured servants.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] As many Virginian settlers began to die from harsh conditions, more and more Africans were brought to work as laborers.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] An indentured servant (who could be White or Black) would work for several years (usually four to seven) without wages.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The status of indentured servants in early Virginia and Maryland was similar to slavery.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Servants could be bought, sold, or leased, and they could be physically beaten for disobedience or attempting to running away.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Unlike slaves, they were freed after their term of service expired or if their freedom was purchased.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Their children did not inherit their status, and on their release from contract they received "a year's provision of corn, double apparel, tools necessary", and a small cash payment called "freedom dues".
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Africans could legally raise crops and cattle to purchase their freedom.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] They raised families, married other Africans and sometimes intermarried with Native Americans or European settlers.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] By the 1640s and 1650s, several African families owned farms around Jamestown, and some became wealthy by colonial standards and purchased indentured servants of their own.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In 1640, the Virginia General Court recorded the earliest documentation of lifetime slavery when they sentenced John Punch, a Negro, to lifetime servitude under his master Hugh Gwyn, for running away.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In Spanish Florida, some Spanish married or had unions with Pensacola, Creek or African women, both enslaved and free, and their descendants created a mixed-race population of mestizos and mulattos.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The Spanish encouraged slaves from the colony of Georgia to come to Florida as a refuge, promising freedom in exchange for conversion to Catholicism.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] King Charles II issued a royal proclamation freeing all slaves who fled to Spanish Florida and accepted conversion and baptism.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Augustine, but escaped slaves also reached Pensacola.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Augustine had mustered an all-Black militia unit defending Spanish Florida as early as 1683.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] One of the Dutch African arrivals, Anthony Johnson, would later own one of the first Black "slaves", John Casor, resulting from the court ruling of a civil case.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The popular conception of a race-based slave system did not fully develop until the 18th century.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The Dutch West India Company introduced slavery in 1625 with the importation of eleven Black slaves into New Amsterdam (present-day New York City).
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] All the colony's slaves, however, were freed upon its surrender to the English.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Massachusetts was the first English colony to legally recognize slavery in 1641.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In 1662, Virginia passed a law that children of enslaved women would take the status of the mother, rather than that of the father, as was the case under common law.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] This legal principle was called *partus sequitur ventrum*.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] By an act of 1699, Virginia ordered the deportation of all free Blacks, effectively defining all people of African descent who remained in the colony as slaves.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In 1670, the colonial assembly passed a law prohibiting free and baptized Blacks (and Native Americans) from purchasing Christians (in this act meaning White Europeans) but allowing them to buy people "of their owne nation".
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In Spanish Louisiana, although there was no movement toward abolition of the African slave trade, Spanish rule introduced a new law called *coartación*, which allowed slaves to buy their freedom, and that of others.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Although some did not have the money to do so, government measures on slavery enabled the existence of many free Blacks.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] This caused problems to the Spaniards with the French creoles (French who had settled in New France) who had also populated Spanish Louisiana.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The French creoles cited that measure as one of the system's worst elements.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] First established in South Carolina in 1704, groups of armed White men—slave patrols—were formed to monitor enslaved Black people.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Their function was to police slaves, especially fugitives.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Slave owners feared that slaves might organize revolts or slave rebellions, so state militias were formed to provide a military command structure and discipline within the slave patrols.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] These patrols were used to detect, encounter, and crush any organized slave meetings which might lead to revolts or rebellions.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The earliest African American congregations and churches were organized before 1800 in both northern and southern cities following the Great Awakening.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] By 1775, Africans made up 20% of the population in the American colonies, which made them the second-largest ethnic group after English Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] During the 1770s, Africans, both enslaved and free, helped rebellious American colonists secure their independence by defeating the British in the American Revolutionary War.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Blacks played a role in both sides in the American Revolution.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Activists in the Patriot cause included James Armistead, Prince Whipple, and Oliver Cromwell.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Around 15,000 Black Loyalists left with the British after the war, most of them ending up as free Black people in England or its colonies, such as the Black Nova Scotians and the Sierra Leone Creole people.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In the Spanish Louisiana, Governor Bernardo de Gálvez organized Spanish free Black men into two militia companies to defend New Orleans during the American Revolution.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] They fought in the 1779 battle in which Spain captured Baton Rouge from the British.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Gálvez also commanded them in campaigns against the British outposts in Mobile, Alabama, and Pensacola, Florida.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] He recruited slaves for the militia by pledging to free anyone who was seriously wounded and promised to secure a low price for *coartación* (buy their freedom and that of others) for those who received lesser wounds.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] During the 1790s, Governor Francisco Luis Héctor, baron of Carondelet reinforced local fortifications and recruit even more free Black men for the militia.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Carondelet doubled the number of free Black men who served, creating two more militia companies—one made up of Black members and the other of pardo (mixed race).
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Serving in the militia brought free Black men one step closer to equality with Whites, allowing them, for example, the right to carry arms and boosting their earning power.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] However, actually these privileges distanced free Black men from enslaved Blacks and encouraged them to identify with Whites.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Slavery had been tacitly enshrined in the US Constitution through provisions such as Article I, Section 2, Clause 3, commonly known as the 3/5 compromise.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Due to the restrictions of Section 9, Clause 1, Congress was unable to pass an Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves until 1807.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Fugitive slave laws (derived from the Fugitive Slave Clause of the Constitution—Article IV, Section 2, Clause 3) were passed by Congress in both 1793 and 1850, guaranteeing the right of a slaveholder to recover an escaped slave anywhere within the US.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Slave owners, who viewed enslaved people as property, ensured that it became a federal crime to aid or assist those who had fled slavery or to interfere with their capture.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] By that time, slavery, which almost exclusively targeted Black people, had become the most critical and contentious political issue in the Antebellum United States, repeatedly sparking crises and conflicts.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Among these were the Missouri Compromise, the Compromise of 1850, the infamous Dred Scott decision, and John Brown's raid on Harpers Ferry.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Prior to the Civil War, eight serving presidents had owned slaves, a practice that was legally protected under the US Constitution.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] By 1860, the number of enslaved Black people in the US had grown to between 3.5 and 4.4 million, largely as a result of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In addition, 488,000–500,000 Black people lived free around the country, with legislated limits imposed upon them in addition to "unconquerable prejudice" from Whites according to Henry Clay.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In response to these conditions, some free Black people chose to leave the US and emigrate to Liberia in West Africa.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Liberia had been established in 1821 as a settlement by the American Colonization Society (ACS), with many abolitionist members of the ACS believing Black Americans would have greater opportunities for freedom and equality in Africa than they would in the US.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Slaves not only represented a significant financial investment for their owners, but they also played a crucial role in producing the country's most valuable product and export: cotton.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Enslaved people were instrumental in the construction of several prominent structures such as, the United States Capitol, the White House and other Washington, D.C.–based buildings.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Similar building projects existed in the slave states.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] By 1815, the domestic slave trade had become a significant and major economic activity in the United States, continuing to flourish until the 1860s.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Historians estimate that nearly one million individuals were subjected to this forced migration, which was often referred to as a new "Middle Passage".
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The historian Ira Berlin described this internal forced migration of enslaved people as the "central event" in the life of a slave during the period between the American Revolution and the Civil War.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Berlin emphasized that whether enslaved individuals were directly uprooted or lived in constant fear that they or their families would be involuntarily relocated, "the massive deportation traumatized Black people" throughout the US.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] As a result of this large-scale forced movement, countless individuals lost their connection to families and clans, and many ethnic Africans lost their knowledge of varying tribal origins in Africa.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Emigration of free Blacks to their continent of origin had been proposed since the Revolutionary war.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] After Haiti became independent, it tried to recruit African Americans to migrate there after it re-established trade relations with the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The Haitian Union was a group formed to promote relations between the countries.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] After riots against Blacks in Cincinnati, its Black community sponsored founding of the Wilberforce Colony, an initially successful settlement of African American immigrants to Canada.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The colony was one of the first such independent political entities.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] It lasted for a number of decades and provided a destination for about 200 Black families emigrating from a number of locations in the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In 1863, during the American Civil War, President Abraham Lincoln signed the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The proclamation declared that all slaves in Confederate-held territory were free.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Advancing Union troops enforced the proclamation, with Texas being the last state to be emancipated, in 1865.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Slavery in a few border states continued until the ratification of the Thirteenth Amendment in December 1865.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] While the Naturalization Act of 1790 limited US citizenship to Whites only, the 14th Amendment (1868) gave Black people citizenship, and the 15th Amendment (1870) gave Black men the right to vote.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] African Americans quickly set up congregations for themselves, as well as schools and community/civic associations, to have space away from White control or oversight.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] While the post-war Reconstruction era was initially a time of progress for African Americans, that period ended in 1876.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] By the late 1890s, Southern states enacted Jim Crow laws to enforce racial segregation and disenfranchisement.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Segregation was now imposed with Jim Crow laws, using signs used to show Blacks where they could legally walk, talk, drink, rest, or eat.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] For those places that were racially mixed, non-Whites had to wait until all White customers were dealt with.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Most African Americans obeyed the Jim Crow laws, to avoid racially motivated violence.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] To maintain self-esteem and dignity, African Americans such as Anthony Overton and Mary McLeod Bethune continued to build their own schools, churches, banks, social clubs, and other businesses.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In the last decade of the 19th century, racially discriminatory laws and racial violence aimed at African Americans began to mushroom in the United States, a period often referred to as the "nadir of American race relations".
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] These discriminatory acts included racial segregation—upheld by the United States Supreme Court decision in *Plessy v.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The desperate conditions of African Americans in the South sparked the Great Migration during the first half of the 20th century which led to a growing African American community in Northern and Western United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The rapid influx of Blacks disturbed the racial balance within Northern and Western cities, exacerbating hostility between both Blacks and Whites in the two regions.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The Red Summer of 1919 was marked by hundreds of deaths and higher casualties across the US as a result of race riots that occurred in more than three dozen cities, such as the Chicago race riot of 1919 and the Omaha race riot of 1919.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Overall, Blacks in Northern and Western cities experienced systemic discrimination in a plethora of aspects of life.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Within employment, economic opportunities for Blacks were routed to the lowest-status and restrictive in potential mobility.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] While many Whites defended their space with violence, intimidation, or legal tactics toward African Americans, many other Whites migrated to more racially homogeneous suburban or exurban regions, a process known as White flight.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Despite discrimination, drawing cards for leaving the hopelessness in the South were the growth of African American institutions and communities in Northern cities.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Institutions included Black oriented organizations (e.g., Urban League, NAACP), churches, businesses, and newspapers, as well as successes in the development in African American intellectual culture, music, and popular culture (e.g., Harlem Renaissance, Chicago Black Renaissance).
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The Cotton Club in Harlem was a Whites-only establishment, with Blacks (such as Duke Ellington) allowed to perform, but to a White audience.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Black Americans also found a new ground for political power in Northern cities, without the enforced disabilities of Jim Crow.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] By the 1950s, the civil rights movement was gaining momentum.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] A 1955 lynching that sparked public outrage about injustice was that of Emmett Till, a 14-year-old boy from Chicago.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Spending the summer with relatives in Money, Mississippi, Till was killed for allegedly having wolf-whistled at a White woman.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Till had been badly beaten, one of his eyes was gouged out, and he was shot in the head.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The visceral response to his mother's decision to have an open-casket funeral mobilized the Black community throughout the US.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Vann Newkirk wrote "the trial of his killers became a pageant illuminating the tyranny of White supremacy".
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The state of Mississippi tried two defendants, but they were speedily acquitted by an all-White jury.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom and the conditions which brought it into being are credited with putting pressure on presidents John F.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] By 1966, the emergence of the Black Power movement, which lasted from 1966 to 1975, expanded upon the aims of the civil rights movement to include economic and political self-sufficiency, and freedom from White authority.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] During the post-war period, many African Americans continued to be economically disadvantaged relative to other Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Average Black income stood at 54 percent of that of White workers in 1947, and 55 percent in 1962.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In 1965, 43 percent of all Black families fell into the poverty bracket, earning under $3,000 (equivalent to $30,649 in 2025) a year.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] The 1960s saw improvements in the social and economic conditions of many Black Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] From 1965 to 1969, Black family income rose from 54 to 60 percent of White family income.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In 1968, 23 percent of Black families earned under $3,000 (equivalent to $27,775 in 2025) a year, compared with 41 percent in 1960.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In 1965, 19 percent of Black Americans had incomes equal to the national median, a proportion that rose to 27 percent by 1967.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In 1960, the median level of education for Blacks had been 10.8 years, and by the late 1960s, the figure rose to 12.2 years, half a year behind the median for Whites.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Politically and economically, African Americans have made substantial strides during the post–civil rights era.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In 1967, Thurgood Marshall became the first African American Supreme Court Justice.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In 1968, Shirley Chisholm became the first Black woman elected to the US Congress.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In 1989, Douglas Wilder became the first African American elected governor in US history.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Clarence Thomas succeeded Marshall to become the second African American Supreme Court Justice in 1991.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In 1992, Carol Moseley-Braun of Illinois became the first African American woman elected to the US Senate.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] There were 8,936 Black officeholders in the United States in 2000, showing a net increase of 7,467 since 1970.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In 2005, the number of Africans immigrating to the United States, in a single year, surpassed the peak number who were involuntarily brought to the United States during the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] On November 4, 2008, Democratic Senator Barack Obama—the son of a White American mother and a Kenyan father—defeated Republican Senator John McCain to become the first African American to be elected president.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] At least 95 percent of African American voters voted for Obama.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] He also received overwhelming support from young and educated Whites, a majority of Asians, and Hispanics, picking up a number of new states in the Democratic electoral column.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Obama lost the overall White vote, although he won a larger proportion of White votes than any previous non-incumbent Democratic presidential candidate since Jimmy Carter.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] Obama was reelected for a second and final term, by a similar margin on November 6, 2012.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In 2021, Kamala Harris, the daughter of a Jamaican father and Indian mother, became the first woman, the first African American, and the first Asian American to serve as Vice President of the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p01] In June 2021, Juneteenth, a day which commemorates the end of slavery in the US, became a federal holiday.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 1790, when the first US census was taken, Africans (including slaves and free people) numbered about 760,000—about 19.3% of the population.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 1860, at the start of the Civil War, the African American population had increased to 4.4 million, but the percentage rate dropped to 14% of the overall population of the country.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The vast majority were slaves, with only 488,000 counted as "freemen".
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] By 1900, the Black population had doubled and reached 8.8 million.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 1910, about 90% of African Americans lived in the South.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Large numbers began migrating north looking for better job opportunities and living conditions, and to escape Jim Crow laws and racial violence.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The Great Migration, as it was called, spanned the 1890s to the 1970s.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] From 1916 through the 1960s, more than six million Black people moved north.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] But in the 1970s and 1980s, that trend reversed, with more African Americans moving south to the Sun Belt than leaving it.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] By 1990, the African American population reached about 30 million and represented 12% of the US population, roughly the same proportion as in 1900.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] At the time of the 2000 US census, 54.8% of African Americans lived in the South.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In that year, 17.6% of African Americans lived in the Northeast and 18.7% in the Midwest, while only 8.9% lived in the Western states.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The west does have a sizable Black population in certain areas, however.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] California, the nation's most populous state, has the fifth-largest African American population, only behind New York, Texas, Georgia, and Florida.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] According to the 2000 census, approximately 2.05% of African Americans identified as Hispanic or Latino in origin, many of whom may be of Brazilian, Puerto Rican, Dominican, Cuban, Haitian, or other Latin American descent.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The only self-reported *ancestral* groups larger than African Americans are the Irish and Germans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] According to the 2010 census, nearly 3% of people who self-identified as Black had recent ancestors who immigrated from another country.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Self-reported non-Hispanic Black immigrants from the Caribbean, mostly from Jamaica and Haiti, represented 0.9% of the US population, at 2.6 million.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Self-reported Black immigrants from sub-Saharan Africa also represented 0.9%, at about 2.8 million.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Additionally, self-identified Black Hispanics represented 0.4% of the United States population, at about 1.2 million people, largely found within the Puerto Rican and Dominican communities.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Self-reported Black immigrants hailing from other countries in the Americas, such as Brazil and Canada, as well as several European countries, represented less than 0.1% of the population.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Mixed-race Hispanic and non-Hispanic Americans who identified as being part Black, represented 0.9% of the population.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Of the 12.6% of United States residents who identified as Black, around 10.3% were "native Black American" or ethnic African Americans, who are direct descendants of West/Central Africans brought to the US as slaves.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] These individuals make up well over 80% of all Blacks in the country.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] When including people of mixed-race origin, about 13.5% of the US population self-identified as Black or "mixed with Black".
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] However, according to the US Census Bureau, evidence from the 2000 census indicates that many African and Caribbean immigrant ethnic groups do not identify as "Black, African Am., or Negro".
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Instead, they wrote in their own respective ethnic groups in the "Some Other Race" write-in entry.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] As a result, the census bureau devised a new, separate "African American" ethnic group category in 2010 for ethnic African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Nigerian Americans and Ethiopian Americans were the most reported sub-Saharan African groups in the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In the 2020 census, the African American population was undercounted at an estimated rate of 3.3%, up from 2.1% in 2010.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Texas has the largest African American population by state with approximately four million.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Followed by Texas is Florida, with 3.8 million, and Georgia, with 3.6 million.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Mississippi is the state with the highest African American share of the population at 39%.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Followed by Mississippi is Louisiana at 34%, and Georgia at 32%.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] After 100 years of African Americans leaving the south in large numbers seeking better opportunities and treatment in the west and north, a movement known as the Great Migration, there is now a reverse trend, called the New Great Migration.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] As with the earlier Great Migration, the New Great Migration is primarily directed toward cities and large urban areas, such as Charlotte, Houston, Dallas, Fort Worth, Huntsville, Raleigh, Tampa, San Antonio, New Orleans, Memphis, Nashville, Jacksonville, and so forth.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] A growing percentage of African Americans from the west and north are migrating to the southern region of the US for economic and cultural reasons.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 2020, New York City, Chicago, and Los Angeles metropolitan areas had the highest decline in African Americans, while Atlanta, Dallas, and Houston had the highest increase respectively.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Despite recent declines, as of 2020, the New York City metropolitan area still has the largest African American metropolitan population in the United States and the only to have over three million African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Among cities of 100,000 or more, South Fulton, Georgia had the highest percentage of Black residents of any large US city in 2020, with 93%.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Claiborne County, Mississippi is the Blackest county in the U.S. at 87% Black in 2020.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Cook County, Illinois has the largest Black population in the U.S. with 1,185,601 Black residents in 2020.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The nation's most affluent community with an African American majority resides in View Park–Windsor Hills, California, with an annual median household income of $159,618 and median home price of about $1.5 million in 2025.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Additionally, there is a significant affluent Black presence in the southern Chicago suburbs of Cook County, Illinois.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 2006, Queens County, New York was the only county with a population of 65,000 or more where African Americans had a higher median household income than White Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Seatack, Virginia is currently the oldest African American community in the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] It survives today with a vibrant and active civic community.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] During slavery, anti-literacy laws were enacted in the US that prohibited education for Black people.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Slave owners saw literacy as a threat to the institution of slavery.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] When slavery was finally abolished in 1865, public educational systems were expanding across the country.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] By 1870, around seventy-four institutions in the south provided a form of advanced education for African American students.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] By 1900, over a hundred programs at these schools provided training for Black professionals, including teachers.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Many of the students at Fisk University, including the young W.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Du Bois, taught school during the summers to support their studies.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African Americans were very concerned to provide quality education for their children, but White supremacy limited their ability to participate in educational policymaking on the political level.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] State governments soon moved to undermine their citizenship by restricting their right to vote.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] By the late 1870s, Blacks were disenfranchised and segregated across the American South.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] White politicians in Mississippi and other states withheld financial resources and supplies from Black schools.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Nevertheless, the presence of Black teachers, and their engagement with their communities both inside and outside the classroom, ensured that Black students had access to education despite these external constraints.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] During World War II, demands for unity and racial tolerance on the home front provided an opening for the first Black history curriculum in the country.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] For example, during the early 1940s, Madeline Morgan, a Black teacher in the Chicago public schools, created a curriculum for students in grades one through eight highlighting the contributions of Black people to the history of the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] At the close of the war, Chicago's Board of Education downgraded the curriculum's status from mandatory to optional.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Predominantly Black schools for kindergarten through twelfth grade students were common throughout the US before the 1970s.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] By 1972, however, desegregation efforts meant that only 25% of Black students were in schools with more than 90% non-White students.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] However, since then, a trend towards re-segregation affected communities across the country: by 2011, 2.9 million African American students were in such overwhelmingly minority schools, including 53% of Black students in school districts that were formerly under desegregation orders.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] As late as 1947, about one third of African Americans over 65 were considered to lack the literacy to read and write their own names.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] By 1969, illiteracy as it had been traditionally defined, had been largely eradicated among younger African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Between 1995 and 2009, freshmen college enrollment for African Americans increased by 73 percent and only 15 percent for Whites.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Black women are enrolled in college more than any other race and gender group, leading all with 9.7% enrolled according to the 2011 US census.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The average high school graduation rate of Blacks in the United States has steadily increased to 71% in 2013.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Separating this statistic into component parts shows it varies greatly depending upon the state and the school district examined.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] 38% of Black males graduated in the state of New York but in Maine 97% graduated and exceeded the White male graduation rate by 11 percentage points.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In much of the southeastern United States and some parts of the southwestern United States the graduation rate of White males was in fact below 70% such as in Florida where 62% of White males graduated from high school.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Examining specific school districts paints an even more complex picture.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In the Detroit school district, the graduation rate of Black males was 20% but 7% for White males.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In the New York City school district 28% of Black males graduate from high school compared to 57% of White males.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In Newark County 76% of Black males graduated compared to 67% for White males.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Further academic improvement has occurred in 2015.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Roughly 23% of all Blacks have bachelor's degrees.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 1988, 21% of Whites had obtained a bachelor's degree versus 11% of Blacks.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 2015, 23% of Blacks had obtained a bachelor's degree versus 36% of Whites.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Foreign born Blacks, 9% of the Black population, made even greater strides.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] They exceed native born Blacks by 10 percentage points.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] College Board, which runs the official college-level advanced placement (AP) programs in American high schools, have has received criticism in recent years that its curricula have focused too much on Euro-centric history.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 2020, College Board reshaped some curricula among history-based courses to further reflect the African diaspora.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 2021, College Board announced it would be piloting an AP African American Studies course between 2022 and 2024.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The course officially launched in August 2024.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In June 2023, the Supreme Court ended race-based affirmative action at American colleges and universities.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In response, many of the nation's most prominent historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs) have reported a significant surge in applications and enrollment.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Slightly more than 250,000 African American students in the high school graduating class of 2025 took the Scholastic Aptitude Test (SAT) making up 13% of test takers.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African American students had an average score of 904 which is lower than the national average of 1,209.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Asian American students had the highest average with 1,229.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] According to a 2025 study, African Americans have the highest average student debt.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African Americans with bachelor's degrees owe an average of $52,726 in student loans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Nearly 70% of African Americans took out a loan to fund their undergraduate education.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African American women, in particular, carry the highest average student debt in the nation.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs), which were founded when segregated institutions of higher learning did not admit African Americans, continue to thrive and educate students of all races today.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] There are 107 HBCUs representing three percent of the nation's colleges and universities with the majority established in the Southeast.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] HBCUs have been largely responsible for establishing and expanding the African American middle-class by providing more career opportunities for African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The economic disparity between the races in the US has marginally improved since the end of slavery.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 1863, two years prior to emancipation, Black people owned 0.5 percent of the national wealth, while in 2019 it is just over 1.5 percent.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Racial disparity in poverty rates has narrowed since the civil rights era, with the poverty rate among African Americans decreasing from 24.7% in 2004 to 18.8% in 2020, compared to 10.5% for all Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Poverty is associated with higher rates of marital stress and dissolution, physical and mental health problems, disability, cognitive deficits, low educational attainment, and crime.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African Americans have a long and diverse history of business ownership.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Although the first African American business is unknown, slaves captured from West Africa are believed to have established commercial enterprises as peddlers and skilled craftspeople as far back as the 17th century.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Washington became the most famous proponent of African American businesses.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] DuBois also commended business as a vehicle for African American advancement.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 2002, African American-owned businesses accounted for 1.2 million of the US's 23 million businesses.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] As of 2011, African American-owned businesses account for approximately two million US businesses.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Black-owned businesses experienced the largest growth in number of businesses among minorities from 2002 to 2011.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Twenty-five percent of Blacks had white-collar occupations (management, professional, and related fields) in 2000, compared with 33.6% of Americans overall.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 2001, over half of African American households of married couples earned $50,000 or more.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Although in the same year African Americans were over-represented among the nation's poor, this was directly related to the disproportionate percentage of African American families headed by single women; such families are collectively poorer, regardless of ethnicity.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 2006, the median earnings of African American men was more than Black and non-Black American women overall, and in all educational levels.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] At the same time, among American men, income disparities were significant; the median income of African American men was approximately 76 cents for every dollar of their European American counterparts, although the gap narrowed somewhat with a rise in educational level.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Overall, the median earnings of African American men were 72 cents for every dollar earned of their Asian American counterparts, and $1.17 for every dollar earned by Hispanic men.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] On the other hand, by 2006, among American women with post-secondary education, African American women have made significant advances; the median income of African American women was more than those of their Asian-, European- and Hispanic American counterparts with at least some college education.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The US public sector is the single most important source of employment for African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] During 2008–2010, 21.2% of all Black workers were public employees, compared with 16.3% of non-Black workers.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Both before and after the onset of the Great Recession, African Americans were 30% more likely than other workers to be employed in the public sector.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The public sector is also a critical source of decent-paying jobs for Black Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] For both men and women, the median wage earned by Black employees is significantly higher in the public sector than in other industries.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 1999, the median income of African American families was $33,255 compared to $53,356 of European Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In times of economic hardship for the nation, African Americans suffer disproportionately from job loss and underemployment, with the Black underclass being hardest hit.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The phrase "last hired and first fired" is reflected in the Bureau of Labor Statistics unemployment figures.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Nationwide, the October 2008 unemployment rate for African Americans was 11.1%, while the nationwide rate was 6.5%.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 2007, the average income for African Americans was approximately $34,000, compared to $55,000 for Whites.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African Americans experience a higher rate of unemployment than the general population.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The income gap between Black and White families is also significant.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 2005, employed Blacks earned 65% of the wages of Whites, down from 82% in 1975.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] *The New York Times* reported in 2006 that in Queens, New York, the median income among African American families exceeded that of White families, which the newspaper attributed to the growth in the number of two-parent Black families.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] It noted that Queens was the only county with more than 65,000 residents where that was true.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 2011, it was reported that 72% of Black babies were born to unwed mothers.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The poverty rate among single-parent Black families was 39.5% in 2005, according to Walter E.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Williams, while it was 9.9% among married-couple Black families.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Among White families, the respective rates were 26.4% and 6% in poverty.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Collectively, African Americans are more involved in the American political process than other minority groups in the United States, indicated by the highest level of voter registration and participation in elections among these groups in 2004.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African Americans also have the highest level of Congressional representation of any minority group in the US.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Homeownership in the US is the strongest indicator of financial stability and the primary asset most Americans use to generate wealth.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African Americans continue to lag behind other racial groups in homeownership.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In the first quarter of 2021, 45.1% of African Americans owned their homes, compared to 65.3% of all Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The African American homeownership rate has remained relatively flat since the 1970s despite an increase in anti-discrimination housing laws and protections.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The African American homeownership rate peaked in 2004 at 49.7%.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The average White high school drop-out still has a slightly better chance of owning a home than the average African American college graduate usually due to unfavorable debt-to-income ratios or credit scores among most African American college graduates.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Since 2000, fast-growing housing costs in most cities have made it even more difficult for the US African American homeownership rate to significantly grow and reach over 50% for the first time in history.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] From 2000 to 2022, the median home price in the US grew 160%, outpacing average annual household income growth in that same period, which only grew about 30%.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] South Carolina is the state with the most African American homeownership, with about 55% of African Americans owning their own homes.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Black people, who make up 12% of the total U.S. population, make up 32% of all people experiencing homelessness, according to the data.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Since the mid 20th century, a large majority of African Americans support the Democratic Party.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In the 2024 Presidential election, 86% of African American voters supported Democrat Kamala Harris, while 13% supported Republican Donald Trump.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Although there is an African American lobby in foreign policy, it has not had the impact that African American organizations have had in domestic policy.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Many African Americans were excluded from electoral politics in the decades following the end of Reconstruction.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The African American trend of voting for Democrats can be traced back to the 1930s during the Great Depression, when Franklin D.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal program provided economic relief to African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal coalition turned the Democratic Party into an organization of the working class and their liberal allies, regardless of region.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The African American vote became even more solidly Democratic when Democratic presidents John F.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Johnson pushed for civil rights legislation during the 1960s.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 1960, nearly a third of African Americans voted for Republican Richard Nixon.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Conservatism has been growing among African Americans, particularly since the 2020 Presidential election.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In the 2024 election, Trump secured a slightly larger share of the African American vote compared to his 2020 performance.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] "Lift Every Voice and Sing" is often referred to as the Black national anthem in the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 1919, the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) had dubbed it the "Negro national anthem" for its power in voicing a cry for liberation and affirmation for African-American people.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The majority of African Americans are Protestant, many of whom follow the historically Black churches.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The term Black church refers to churches which minister to predominantly African American congregations.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Black congregations were first established by freed slaves at the end of the 17th century, and later when slavery was abolished more African Americans were allowed to create a unique form of Christianity that was culturally influenced by African spiritual traditions.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] According to a 2007 survey, more than half of the African American population are part of the historically Black churches.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The largest Protestant denomination among African Americans is the Baptists, distributed mainly in four denominations, the largest being the National Baptist Convention, USA and the National Baptist Convention of America.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The second-largest is the Methodists, the largest organizations of which are the African Methodist Episcopal Church and the African Methodist Episcopal Zion Church.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Pentecostals are distributed among several different religious bodies, with the Church of God in Christ as the largest among them by far.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] About 16% of African American Christians are members of White Protestant communions; these denominations (which include the United Church of Christ) mostly have a 2–3% African American membership.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] There are also large numbers of Catholics, constituting 5% of the African American population.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Of the total number of Jehovah's Witnesses, 22% are Black.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Historically, between 15 and 30% of enslaved Africans brought to the Americas were Muslims, but most of these Africans were converted to Christianity during the era of American slavery.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Prominent members included activist Malcolm X and boxer Muhammad Ali.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Malcolm X is considered the first person to start the movement among African Americans towards mainstream Islam, after he left the Nation and made the pilgrimage to Mecca.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 1975, Warith Deen Mohammed, the son of Elijah Muhammad took control of the Nation after his father's death and guided the majority of its members to orthodox Islam.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African American Muslims constitute 20% of the total US Muslim population, the majority are Sunni or orthodox Muslims, some of these identify under the community of W.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The Nation of Islam led by Louis Farrakhan has a membership ranging from 20,000 to 50,000 members.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] There is also a small but growing group of African American Jews, making up less than 0.5% of African Americans or about 2% of the Jewish population in the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The majority of African-American Jews are Ashkenazi, while smaller numbers identify as Sephardi, Mizrahi, or other.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Many African-American Jews are affiliated with denominations such as the Reform, Conservative, Reconstructionist, or Orthodox branches of Judaism, but the majority identify as "Jews of no religion", commonly known as secular Jews.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] A significant number of people who identify themselves as "Black Jews" are affiliated with syncretic religious groups, largely the Black Hebrew Israelites, whose beliefs include the claim that African Americans are descended from the Biblical Israelites.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Jews of all races typically do not accept Black Hebrew Israelites as Jews, in part because they are usually not Jewish according to Jewish law, and in part because these groups are sometimes associated with antisemitism.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African-American Jews have criticized the Black Hebrew Israelites, regarding the movement as primarily composed of Black non-Jews who have appropriated Black-Jewish identity.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In the 2010s, confirmed atheists were less than one half of one percent, similar to numbers for Hispanics.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 2025, a Pew Research Center study found that, among Black Americans, Christian affiliation has declined in recent years.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The share of Black adults identifying as Christian fell from 85% in 2007 to 79% in 2014 and 73% in 2021, mirroring a broader decline in Christianity in the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] However, Black adults remain more likely than U.S. adults overall to identify as Christian (73% vs.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] By comparison, about half or fewer adults in other racial or ethnic groups report that religion is very important or that they pray daily, and even smaller shares attend services monthly.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Religiosity among Black Americans also varies by age.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] 39% of Black adults aged 65 and older describe themselves as very religious, compared with 21% of those under 30.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] This age pattern is similar to that observed among White and Hispanic Americans, although Black adults of all ages are more likely than other groups to describe themselves as very religious.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] According to a Gallup survey, 4.6% of Black or African Americans self-identified as LGBT in 2016, while the total portion of American adults in all ethnic groups identifying as LGBT was 4.1% in 2016.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African American women are more likely than African American men to openly identify as LGBT.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The life expectancy for Black men in 2008 was 70.8 years.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Life expectancy for Black women was 77.5 years in 2008.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 1900, when information on Black life expectancy started being collated, a Black man could expect to live to 32.5 years and a Black woman 33.5 years.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 1900, White men lived an average of 46.3 years and White women lived an average of 48.3 years.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African American life expectancy at birth is persistently five to seven years lower than European Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Black men have shorter lifespans than any other group in the US besides Native American men.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Black people have higher rates of obesity, diabetes, and hypertension than the US average.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] For adult Black men, the rate of obesity was 31.6% in 2010.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] For adult Black women, the rate of obesity was 41.2% in 2010.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African Americans have higher rates of mortality than any other racial or ethnic group for eight of the top ten causes of death.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 2013, among men, Black men had the highest rate of getting cancer, followed by White, Hispanic, Asian/Pacific Islander (A/PI), and American Indian/Alaska Native (AI/AN) men.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Among women, White women had the highest rate of getting cancer, followed by Black, Hispanic, Asian/Pacific Islander, and American Indian/Alaska Native women.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African Americans also have higher prevalence and incidence of Alzheimer's disease compared to the overall average.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Black women lead the nation in abortions.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] According to a 2022 report, Black women made up 40% of abortions despite making up 13% of the U.S. woman population.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African Americans are more likely than White Americans to die due to health-related problems developed by alcoholism.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Alcohol abuse is the main contributor to the top three causes of death among African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In December 2020, African Americans were less likely to be vaccinated against COVID-19 due to mistrust in the US medical system.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] From 2021 to 2022, there was an increase in African Americans who became vaccinated.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Still, in 2022, COVID-19 complications became the third leading cause of death for African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Violence is a major problem within the African American community.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] A report from the US Department of Justice states "In 2005, homicide victimization rates for Blacks were more than six times as high as the rates for Whites".
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The report also found that "94% of Black victims were killed by Blacks." Of the nearly 20,000 recorded US homicides in 2022, African Americans made up the majority of offenders and victims despite making up less than 15% of the population.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 2024, all of the five most dangerous US cities have a significant Black population and highly concerning Black-on-Black violent crime rate.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Black males age 15–44 are the only race/sex category for which homicide is a top-five cause of death.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Black women are three times more likely to be killed by an intimate partner than White women.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Black children are more than three times as likely to die due to parental abuse and neglect than White children.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, African Americans have higher rates of sexually transmitted infections (STIs) compared to Whites, with five times the rates of syphilis and chlamydia, and 7.5 times the rate of gonorrhea.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The disproportionately high incidence of HIV/AIDS among African Americans has been attributed to homophobic influences, lack of condom usage, and lack of proper healthcare.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The prevalence of HIV/AIDS among Black men is seven times higher than the prevalence for White men, and Black men are more than nine times as likely to die from HIV/AIDS-related illness than White men.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The prevalence of HIV/AIDS among Black women is 20 times higher than White women, and Black women are more than 15 times as likely to die from HIV/AIDS-related illness than White women.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African Americans have several barriers for accessing mental health services.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Counseling has been frowned upon and distant in utility and proximity to many people in the African American community.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 2004, a qualitative research study explored the disconnect with African Americans and mental health.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The study was conducted as a semi-structured discussion which allowed the focus group to express their opinions and life experiences.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] The results revealed a couple key variables that create barriers for many African American communities to seek mental health services such as the stigma, lack of four important necessities; trust, affordability, cultural understanding and impersonal services.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Historically, many African American communities did not seek counseling because religion was a part of the family values.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African Americans who have a faith background are more likely to seek prayer as a coping mechanism for mental issues rather than seeking professional mental health services.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 2015 a study concluded, African Americans with high value in religion are less likely to utilize mental health services compared to those who have low value in religion.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In the United States, counseling approaches are based on the experience of White Americans and do not fit within the African American culture.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] African American families tend to resolve concerns within the family, and it is viewed by the family as a strength.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] On the other hand, when African Americans seek counseling, they face a social backlash and are criticized.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] They may be labeled "crazy", viewed as weak, and their pride is diminished.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Because of this, many African Americans instead seek mentorship within communities they trust.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Terminology is another barrier in relation to African Americans and mental health.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] There is more stigma on the term *psychotherapy* versus counseling.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In one study, psychotherapy is associated with mental illness whereas counseling approaches problem-solving, guidance and help.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] More African Americans seek assistance when it is called counseling and not psychotherapy because it is more welcoming within the culture and community.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Counselors are encouraged to be aware of such barriers for the well-being of African American clients.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] Without cultural competency training in health care, many African Americans go unheard and misunderstood.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] In 2021, African Americans had the third highest suicide rate trailing American Indians/Alaska Natives and White Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] However, African Americans had the second highest increase of its suicide rate from 2011 to 2021, growing 58%.
[src:trousers/african-american-p02] As of 2024, suicide is the second leading cause of death among African-Americans between the ages of 15 and 24, with Black men being four times more likely to kill themselves than Black women.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Recent studies of African Americans using genetic testing have found ancestry to vary by region and sex of ancestors.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] These studies found that on average, African Americans have 73.2–82.1% Sub-Saharan African, 16.7–24% European, and 0.8–1.2% Native American genetic ancestry, with large variation between individuals.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Commercial testing services have reported similar variation, with ranges from 0.6 to 2 percent Native American, 19 to 29 percent European, and 65 to 80 percent Sub-Saharan African ancestry.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] According to a genome-wide study by Bryc et al.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] (2009), the mixed ancestry of African Americans in varying ratios came about as the result of sexual contact between West/Central Africans (more frequently females) and Europeans (more frequently males).
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] This can be understood as being the result of enslaved African American females being raped by White males.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Consequently, the 365 African Americans in their sample have a genome-wide average of 78.1% West African ancestry and 18.5% European ancestry, with large variation among individuals (ranging from 99% to 1% West African ancestry).
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The West African ancestral component in African Americans is most similar to that in present-day speakers from the non-Bantu branches of the Niger-Congo family.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] (2014) observed that around 50% of the overall ancestry of African Americans traces comes from a population similar to the Niger-Congo-speaking Yoruba of southern Nigeria and southern Benin, reflecting the centrality of this West African region in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The next most frequent ancestral component found among African Americans was derived from Great Britain, in keeping with historical records.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] It constitutes a little over 10% of their overall ancestry and is most similar to the Northwest European ancestral component also carried by Barbadians.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] (2009) found a similar proportion of Yoruba-like ancestry in their African American samples, with a minority also drawn from Mandenka and Bantu populations.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Additionally, the researchers observed an average European ancestry of 21.9%, again with significant variation between individuals.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] (2009) note that populations from other parts of the continent may also constitute adequate proxies for the ancestors of some African American individuals; namely, ancestral populations from Guinea Bissau, Senegal and Sierra Leone in West Africa and Angola in Southern Africa.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] An individual African American person can have over fifteen African ethnic groups in their genetic makeup alone due to the slave trade covering such vast areas.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Altogether, genetic studies suggest that African Americans are a genetically diverse people.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] According to DNA analysis led in 2006 by Penn State geneticist Mark D.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] According to Shriver, around five percent of African Americans also have at least 12.5% Native American ancestry (equivalent to one Native American great-grandparent and their forebears).
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Research suggests that Native American ancestry among people who identify as African American is a result of relationships that occurred soon after slave ships arrived in the American colonies, and European ancestry is of more recent origin, often from the decades before the Civil War.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Africans bearing the E-V38 (E1b1a) likely traversed across the Sahara, from east to west, approximately 19,000 years ago.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] E-M2 (E1b1a1) likely originated in West Africa or Central Africa.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] According to a Y-DNA study by Sims et al.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] (2007), the majority (≈60%) of African Americans belong to various subclades of the E-M2 (E1b1a1, formerly E3a) paternal haplogroup.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] This is the most common genetic paternal lineage found today among West/Central African males and is also a signature of the historical Bantu migrations.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The next most frequent Y-DNA haplogroup observed among African Americans is the R1b clade, which around 15% of African Americans carry.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] This lineage is most common today among Northwestern European males.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The remaining African Americans mainly belong to the paternal haplogroup I (≈7%), which is also frequent in Northwestern Europe.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] According to an mtDNA study by Salas et al.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] (2005), the maternal lineages of African Americans are most similar to haplogroups that are today especially common in West Africa (>55%), followed closely by West-Central Africa and Southwestern Africa (<41%).
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The characteristic West African haplogroups L1b, L2b,c,d, and L3b,d and West-Central African haplogroups L1c and L3e in particular occur at high frequencies among African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] As with the paternal DNA of African Americans, contributions from other parts of the continent to their maternal gene pool are insignificant.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Formal political, economic and social discrimination against minorities has been present throughout American history.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Saito, Associate Professor of Sociology and American Studies & Ethnicity at the University of Southern California, writes, "Political rights have been circumscribed by race, class and gender since the founding of the United States, when the right to vote was restricted to White men of property.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Those who economically gained the most from slavery were the planter class, owners of large-scale plantations where large numbers of enslaved Africans were held captive and forced to produce crops to create wealth for a White elite.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Although they have gained a greater degree of social equality since the civil rights movement, African Americans have remained stagnant economically, which has hindered their ability to break into the middle class and beyond.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] As of 2020, the racial wealth gap between Whites and Blacks remains as large as it was in 1968, with the typical net worth of a White household equivalent to that of 11.5 Black households.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Despite this, African Americans have increased employment rates and gained representation in the highest levels of American government in the post–civil rights era.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] However, widespread racism remains an issue that continues to undermine the development of social status.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Economically, of all the racially Black ethnic groups on the globe, African Americans are the wealthiest and most successful, with one in every fifty African American families being millionaires.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] This equates in 2023 to approximately 1.79 million African American millionaires in the United States, which is more than the number of millionaires in any racially Black country, and many other countries, around the world.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] In the US, which has the largest per-capita prison population in the world, African Americans are overrepresented as the second-largest population of prison inmates (38%) in 2023, coming second to Whites, who made up 57% of the prison population.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] According to the National Registry of Exonerations, Blacks are roughly 7.5 times more likely to be wrongfully convicted of murder in the US than Whites.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] In 2012, the New York City Police Department detained people more than 500,000 times under the city's stop-and-frisk law.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Of the total detained, 55% were African-Americans, while Black people made up 20% of the city's population.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] African American males are more likely to be killed by police when compared to other races.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] This is one of the factors that led to the creation of the Black Lives Matter movement in 2013.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] According to *The Guardian*, "The specter of Karen persisted as Black Lives Matter protests and civil unrest spread around the country following Floyd's murder and reckonings with racism began to roil institutions, toppling careers as well as statues".
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] In the aftermath of the peak Black Lives Matter protests and widespread police reform efforts in the early 2020s, crime rates surged across the nation, especially in predominantly Black neighborhoods.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Many cities experienced near-record or record levels of violence and other criminal activity.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] As a result, numerous municipalities scaled back police reform initiatives and increased funding for law enforcement.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] After over 50 years, marriage rates for all Americans began to decline while divorce rates and out-of-wedlock births have climbed.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] These changes have been greatest among African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] After more than 70 years of racial parity Black marriage rates began to fall behind Whites.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Single-parent households have become most common, and according to US census figures released in January 2010, only 38% of Black children lived with both their parents.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] In 2021, statistics show that over 80% marriages in the African American ethnic group marry within their ethnic group.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Black children are overrepresented in the U.S. foster care system.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] In 2017, Black American children made up 14% of the children population but 22% of those in the foster care system.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Black American children are more than twice as likely to be placed in foster care than White American children.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The first ever anti-miscegenation law was passed by the Maryland General Assembly in 1691, criminalizing interracial marriage.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] In a speech in Charleston, Illinois in 1858, Abraham Lincoln stated, "I am not, nor ever have been in favor of making voters or jurors of negroes, nor of qualifying them to hold office, nor to intermarry with white people".
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] By the late 1800s, 38 US states had anti-miscegenation statutes.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] By 1924, the ban on interracial marriage was still in force in 29 states.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] While interracial marriage had been legal in California since 1948, in 1957 actor Sammy Davis Jr. faced a backlash for his involvement with White actress Kim Novak.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Harry Cohn, the president of Columbia Pictures, with whom Novak was under contract, gave in to his concerns that a racist backlash against the relationship could hurt the studio.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Davis briefly married Black dancer Loray White in 1958 to protect himself from mob violence.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Inebriated at the wedding ceremony, Davis despairingly said to his best friend, Arthur Silber Jr., "Why won't they let me live my life?" The couple never lived together, and commenced divorce proceedings in September 1958.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] In 1967 the law was ruled unconstitutional (via the 14th Amendment adopted in 1868) by the US Supreme Court in *Loving v.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] In 2008, Democrats overwhelmingly voted 70% against California Proposition 8, African Americans voted 58% in favor of it while 42% voted against Proposition 8.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] On May 9, 2012, Barack Obama, the first Black president, became the first US president to support same-sex marriage.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Since Obama's endorsement there has been a rapid growth in support for same-sex marriage among African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] As of 2012, 59% of African Americans support same-sex marriage, which is higher than support among the national average (53%) and White Americans (50%).
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Polls in North Carolina, Pennsylvania, Missouri, Maryland, Ohio, Florida, and Nevada have also shown an increase in support for same sex marriage among African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] On November 6, 2012, Maryland, Maine, and Washington all voted for approve of same-sex marriage, along with Minnesota rejecting a constitutional amendment banning same-sex marriage.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Exit polls in Maryland show about 50% of African Americans voted for same-sex marriage, showing a vast evolution among African Americans on the issue and was crucial in helping pass same-sex marriage in Maryland.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Black Americans hold far more conservative opinions on abortion, extramarital sex, and raising children out of wedlock than Democrats as a whole.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] On financial issues, however, African Americans are in line with Democrats, generally supporting a more progressive tax structure to provide more government spending on social services.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] African Americans have fought in every war in the history of the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The gains made by African Americans in the civil rights movement and in the Black Power movement not only obtained certain rights for African Americans but changed American society in far-reaching and fundamentally important ways.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Prior to the 1950s, Black Americans in the South were subject to de jure discrimination, or Jim Crow laws.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] They were often the victims of extreme cruelty and violence, sometimes resulting in deaths: by the post World War II era, African Americans became increasingly discontented with their long-standing inequality.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The civil rights movement marked an enormous change in American social, political, economic and civic life.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Over time, it has changed in fundamental ways the manner in which Blacks and Whites interact with and relate to one another.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Some activists and academics contend that American news media coverage of African American news, concerns, or dilemmas is inadequate, or that the news media present distorted images of African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Johnson founded Black Entertainment Television (BET), a network that targets young African Americans and urban audiences in the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Over the years, the network has aired such programming as rap and R&B music videos, urban-oriented movies and television series, and some public affairs programs.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] On Sunday mornings, BET would broadcast Christian programming; the network would also broadcast non-affiliated Christian programs during the early morning hours daily.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] According to Viacom, BET is now a global network that reaches households in the United States, Caribbean, Canada, and the United Kingdom.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The network has gone on to spawn several spin-off channels, including BET Her (originally launched as *BET on Jazz*).
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Another network targeting African Americans is TV One.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] TV One is owned by Urban One, founded and controlled by Catherine Hughes.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Urban One is one of the nation's largest radio broadcasting companies and the largest African American-owned radio broadcasting company in the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] In June 2009, NBC News launched a new website named TheGrio.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] It is the first African American video news site that focuses on underrepresented stories in existing national news.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] From their earliest presence in North America, African Americans have significantly contributed literature, art, agricultural skills, cuisine, clothing styles, music, language, and social and technological innovation to American culture.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The cultivation and use of many agricultural products in the United States, such as yams, peanuts, rice, okra, sorghum, grits, watermelon, indigo dyes, and cotton, can be traced to West African and African American influences.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Notable examples include George Washington Carver, who created nearly 500 products from peanuts, sweet potatoes, and pecans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Soul food is a variety of cuisine popular among African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] It is closely related to the cuisine of the Southern United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The descriptive terminology may have originated in the mid-1960s, when *soul* was a common definer used to describe African American culture (for example, soul music).
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] African Americans were the first peoples in the United States to make fried chicken, along with Scottish immigrants to the South.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Although the Scottish had been frying chicken before they emigrated, they lacked the spices and flavor that African Americans had used when preparing the meal.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The Scottish American settlers therefore adopted the African American method of seasoning chicken.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] However, fried chicken was generally a rare meal in the African American community and was usually reserved for special events or celebrations.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] African-American English is a variety (dialect, ethnolect, and sociolect) of American English, commonly spoken by urban working-class and largely bi-dialectal middle-class African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] It shares parts of its grammar and phonology with the Southern American English dialect.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] African American English differs from Standard American English (SAE) in certain pronunciation characteristics, tense usage, and grammatical structures, which were derived from West African languages (particularly those belonging to the Niger–Congo family).
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Virtually all habitual speakers of African American English can understand and communicate in Standard American English.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] As with all linguistic forms, AAVE's usage is influenced by various factors, including geographical, educational and socioeconomic background, as well as formality of setting.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Additionally, there are many literary uses of this variety of English, particularly in African American literature.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Other languages are spoken by specific sub-communities.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The Gullah language is an English-based creole language spoken mostly in the coastal regions of South Carolina and Georgia by the Gullah; an off-shoot of this is Afro-Seminole Creole spoken by Black Seminoles mostly now in Mexico and Brackettville, Texas.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Louisiana Creole is a French-based creole and spoken mostly in Louisiana.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] African-American names are part of the cultural traditions of African Americans, most of these cultural names having no connection to Africa but strictly an African American cultural practice that developed in the United States during enslavement.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] This new evidence became apparent by census records which show African Americans and White Americans, though they spoke the same language, chose to use different names even during times of enslavement, which is where and when the development of African American cultural names began.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Prior to this newer information, it was only thought that before the 1950s, and 1960s, most African-American names closely resembled those used within European-American culture.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Babies of that era were generally given a few common names, with children using nicknames to distinguish the various people with the same name.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] With the rise of 1960s civil rights movement, there was a dramatic increase in names of various origins.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] By the 1970s, and 1980s, it had become common among African Americans to invent new names for themselves, although many of these invented names took elements from popular existing names.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Prefixes such as La/Le, Da/De, Ra/Re and Ja/Je, and suffixes like -ique/iqua, -isha and -aun/-awn are common, as are inventive spellings for common names.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The book *Baby Names Now: From Classic to Cool—The Very Last Word on First Names* places the origins of "La" names in African-American culture in New Orleans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Even with the rise of inventive names, it is still common for African Americans to use biblical, historical, or traditional European names.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Daniel, Christopher, Michael, David, James, Joseph, and Matthew were thus among the most frequent names for African-American boys in 2013.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The name LaKeisha is typically considered American in origin but has elements that were drawn from both French and West/Central African roots.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Names such as LaTanisha, JaMarcus, DeAndre, and Shaniqua were created in the same way.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Punctuation marks are seen more often within African American names than other American names, such as the names Mo'nique and D'Andre.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] African American music is one of the most pervasive African American cultural influences in the United States today and is among the most dominant in mainstream popular music.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Hip-hop, R&B, funk, rock and roll, soul, blues, and other contemporary American musical forms originated in Black communities and evolved from other Black forms of music, including blues, doo-wop, barbershop, ragtime, bluegrass, jazz, and gospel music.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] African American-derived musical forms have also influenced and been incorporated into virtually every other popular music genre in the world, including country and techno.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] African Americans have also had an important role in American dance.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Jones, a prominent modern choreographer and dancer, has included historical African American themes in his work, particularly in the piece "Last Supper at Uncle Tom's Cabin/The Promised Land".
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Likewise, Alvin Ailey's artistic work, including his "Revelations" based on his experience growing up as an African American in the South during the 1930s, has had a significant influence on modern dance.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Another form of dance, stepping, is an African American tradition whose performance and competition has been formalized through the traditionally Black fraternities and sororities at universities.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Discussions of race and sports in the United States, where the two subjects have always been intertwined in American history, have focused to a great extent on African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Depending on the type of sport and performance level, African Americans are reported to be over- or under-represented.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] African Americans compose the highest percentage of the minority groups active at the professional level, but are among those who show the lowest participation overall.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] And though the list of African Americans in professional sports remains high, it only represents a small fraction of aspiring black athletes.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Many African American authors have written stories, poems, and essays influenced by their experiences as African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] African American literature is a major genre in American literature.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Famous examples include Langston Hughes, James Baldwin, Richard Wright, Zora Neale Hurston, Ralph Ellison, Nobel Prize winner Toni Morrison, and Maya Angelou.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] African American inventors have created many widely used devices in the world and have contributed to international innovation.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Norbert Rillieux created the technique for converting sugar cane juice into white sugar crystals.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Moreover, Rillieux left Louisiana in 1854 and went to France, where he spent ten years working with the Champollions deciphering Egyptian hieroglyphics from the Rosetta Stone.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Most slave inventors were nameless, such as the slave owned by the Confederate President Jefferson Davis who designed the ship propeller used by the Confederate navy.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] By 1913, over 1,000 inventions were patented by Black Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Among the most notable inventors were Jan Matzeliger, who developed the first machine to mass-produce shoes, and Elijah McCoy, who invented automatic lubrication devices for steam engines.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Granville Woods had 35 patents to improve electric railway systems, including the first system to allow moving trains to communicate.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Morgan developed the first automatic traffic signal and gas mask.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Lewis Howard Latimer invented an improvement for the incandescent light bulb.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] More recent inventors include Frederick McKinley Jones, who invented the movable refrigeration unit for food transport in trucks and trains.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Lloyd Quarterman worked with six other Black scientists on the creation of the atomic bomb (code named the Manhattan Project) and helped develop the first nuclear reactor.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] As part of the preservation of their culture, African Americans have continuously launched their own publications and publishing houses, such as Robert Sengstacke Abbott, founder of the Chicago Defender newspaper, and Carter G.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Woodson, the founder of Black History Month who spent over thirty years documenting and publishing African American history in journals and books.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The Johnson Publishing Company, founded by John H.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Johnson in 1942, is a National Historic Landmark.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The term *African American* was popularized by Jesse Jackson in the 1980s, although there are recorded uses from the 18th and 19th centuries, for example, in post-emancipation holidays and conferences.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Earlier terms also used to describe Americans of African ancestry referred more to skin color than to ancestry.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Other terms (such as *colored*, *person of color*, or *negro*) were included in the wording of various laws and legal decisions which some thought were being used as tools of White supremacy and oppression.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] A 16-page pamphlet entitled "A Sermon on the Capture of Lord Cornwallis" is notable for the attribution of its authorship to "An *African American*".
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Published in 1782, the book's use of this phrase predates any other yet identified by more than 50 years.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] In the 1980s, the term *African American* was advanced to give descendants of American slaves, and other American Blacks who lived through the slavery era, a heritage and a cultural base.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The term was popularized in Black communities around the country via word of mouth and ultimately received mainstream use after Jesse Jackson's use in 1988.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Subsequently, major media outlets adopted it.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Surveys in the 1990s and the first decade of the 21st century showed that the majority of Black Americans had no preference for *African American* versus *Black American*, although they had a slight preference for the latter in personal settings and the former in more formal settings.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] By 2021, according to polling from Gallup, 58% of Black Americans expressed no preference for what their group should be called, with 17% each preferring *Black* and *African-American*.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] In 2023, the government released a new more detailed breakdown due to the rise in racially Black immigration into the US, listing African American as a compound termed ethnicity, distinguished from other racially Black ethnicities such as Nigerian, Jamaican etc.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The term *African American* embraces pan-Africanism as earlier enunciated by prominent African thinkers such as Marcus Garvey, W.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The term *Afro-Usonian*, and variations of such, are more rarely used.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] In preparation for the 2010 US census, a marketing and outreach plan called *2010 Census Integrated Communications Campaign Plan* (ICC) recognized and defined African Americans as Black people born in the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] From the ICC perspective, African Americans are one of three groups of Black people in the United States: African Americans, Black Africans, and Afro-Caribbeans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The ICC plan was to reach the three groups by acknowledging that each group has its own sense of community that is based on geography and ethnicity.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The best way to market the census process toward any of the three groups is to reach them through their own unique communication channels and not treat the entire Black population of the US as though they are all African Americans with a single ethnic and geographical background.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Historically, "race mixing" between Black and White people was taboo in the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] So-called anti-miscegenation laws, barring Blacks and Whites from marrying or having sex, were established in colonial America as early as 1691, and endured in many Southern states until the Supreme Court ruled them unconstitutional in *Loving v.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The taboo among American Whites surrounding White-Black relations is a historical consequence of the oppression and racial segregation of African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Harvard University historian Henry Louis Gates Jr. wrote in 2009 that "African Americans...are a racially mixed or mulatto people—deeply and overwhelmingly so".
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] After the Emancipation Proclamation, Chinese American men married African American women in high proportions to their total marriage numbers due to few Chinese American women being in the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] African slaves and their descendants have also had a history of cultural exchange and intermarriage with Native Americans, although they did not necessarily retain social, cultural or linguistic ties to Native peoples.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] There are also increasing intermarriages and offspring between non-Hispanic Blacks and Hispanics of any race, especially between Puerto Ricans and African Americans.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Racially mixed marriages have become increasingly accepted in the United States since the civil rights movement.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] A Gallup poll conducted in 2013 found that 84% of Whites and 96% of Blacks approved of interracial marriage, and 87% overall.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Black men are more than twice as likely to date and marry interracially than Black women.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] At the end of World War II, some African American military men stationed in Asia and Europe impregnated local non-Black women, resulting in the birth of thousands of mixed-race children called "Brown Babies".
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Some of these families later immigrated to the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] However, some mixed-race children, especially in Japan, were placed in orphanages due to social stigmas associated with half-Black fatherless children in the 1950s.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Author Debra Dickerson has argued that the term *Black* should refer strictly to the descendants of Africans who were brought to America as slaves, and not to the sons and daughters of Black immigrants who lack that ancestry.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Thus, under her definition, President Barack Obama, who is the son of a Kenyan, is not Black.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] "Lumping us all together", Dickerson wrote, "erases the significance of slavery and continuing racism while giving the appearance of progress." Similar comments have been made concerning Kamala Harris, the daughter of a Jamaican immigrant, who was elected vice president in 2020.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The American Descendants of Slavery (ADOS) movement coalesces around this view, arguing that Black descendants of American slavery deserve a separate ethnic category that distinguishes them from other Black groups in the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Their terminology has gained popularity in some circles, but others have criticized the movement for a perceived bias against (especially poor and Black) immigrants, and for its often inflammatory rhetoric.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Politicians such as Obama and Harris have received especially pointed criticism from the movement, as neither are ADOS and have spoken out at times against policies specific to them.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Most notably, Malcolm X and Kwame Ture expressed similar views that African Americans are Africans who "happen to be in America", and should not claim or identify as being American if they are fighting for Black (New Afrikan) liberation.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Historically, this is due to the enslavement of Africans during the transatlantic slave trade, ongoing anti-Black violence, and structural racism in countries like the United States.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Before the independence of the Thirteen Colonies until the abolition of slavery in 1865, an African American slave was commonly known as a *negro*.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] *Free negro* was the legal status in the territory of an African American person who was not enslaved.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The term was used until the second quarter of the 20th century, when it was considered outmoded – although it was retained in the name of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) – and generally gave way again to the exclusive use of *negro*.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] By the 1940s, the term was commonly capitalized (*Negro*); but by the mid-1960s, it was considered disparaging.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] By the end of the 20th century, *negro* had come to be considered inappropriate and was rarely used and perceived as a pejorative.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The term is rarely used by younger Black people, but remained in use by many older African Americans who had grown up with the term, particularly in the Southern US.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The term remains in use in some contexts, such as the United Negro College Fund, an American philanthropic organization.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] There are many other deliberately insulting terms, many of which were in common use (e.g., *nigger*), but had become unacceptable in normal discourse before the end of the 20th century.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] One exception is the use, among the Black community, of the slur *nigger* rendered as *nigga*, representing the pronunciation of the word in African American English.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] This usage has been popularized by American rap and hip-hop music cultures and is used as part of an in-group lexicon and speech.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] It is not necessarily derogatory and, when used among Black people, the word is often used to mean "homie" or "friend".
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] Acceptance of intra-group usage of the word *nigga* is still debated, although it has established a foothold among younger generations.
[src:trousers/african-american-p03] The NAACP denounces the use of both *nigga* and *nigger*.
[src:trousers/alabastron] An **alabastron** /ˌæləˈbæstrən, -ˌtrɒn/ or **alabastrum** /ˌæləˈbæstrəm/ (Ancient Greek: ἀλάβαστρον or ἀλάβαστος; plural: *alabastra* or *alabastri* (ἀλάβαστρα or ἀλάβαστα)) is a small tapering or pear-shaped vessel, having no feet, used for holding perfumes or massage oils.
[src:trousers/alabastron] They originated around the 11th century BC in ancient Egypt and spread via ancient Greece to other parts of the classical world.
[src:trousers/alabastron] The first mention of such scent bottles comes from Herodotus, who refers to a myrrh alabastron (μύρου ἀλάβαστρο) as one of the gifts sent by Cambyses to the king of Ethiopia.
[src:trousers/alabastron] They were originally crafted from alabaster, particularly the onyx-alabaster variety, which was commonly used for this purpose.
[src:trousers/alabastron] However, it's uncertain whether the vessels were named after the material or if the material was named after the vessels.
[src:trousers/alabastron] They can also be made from stone and terra-cotta, with other materials like glass and even gold (χρύσεια ἀλάβαστρα) being used as well.
[src:trousers/alabastron] Most types of alabastron have a narrow body with a rounded end, a narrow neck and a broad, splayed mouth.
[src:trousers/alabastron] They were often left without handles, but some types were equipped with ear-shaped projections or lugs into which holes were punched.
[src:trousers/alabastron] Strings were then put through these holes for easy mobility.
[src:trousers/alabastron] The design of the first Egyptian alabastra was inspired by the palm tree, with a columnar shape, a palm capital and a stand.
[src:trousers/alabastron] Later designs were made from glass decorated with various patterns, such as scallops, festoons, or abstract patterns of rings or zigzags.
[src:trousers/alabastron] Around the 7th century BC, alabastra spread to Greece and became an important element of ancient Greek pottery.
[src:trousers/alabastron] Alabastra also appeared in many other places in the ancient world, notably Assyria, Syria and Palestine, all having presumably been inspired by or exported from Greece or Egypt.
[src:trousers/alabastron] Within a hundred years after arriving in the area, Greek artisans were producing elaborately decorated silver alabastra, long and narrow and 12–16 centimeters (4.7–6.3 in) in height.
[src:trousers/alabastron] The decoration usually involved dividing the body of the vase into four horizontal zones by ornamental bands around it.
[src:trousers/alabastron] An **alabastrotheca** (ἀλαβαστροθήκη or ἀλαβαστοθήκη) was a box or casket for storing alabastra or a holder used to keep the bottles upright when not in use, as their rounded bottoms made them unable to stand on their own.
[src:trousers/amazons] In Greek mythology, the **Amazons** (Ancient Greek: Ἀμαζόνες) were female warriors and hunters, known for their physical agility, strength, archery, riding skills, and the arts of combat.
[src:trousers/amazons] Their society was closed to men and they raised only their daughters, returning their sons to their fathers with whom they would only socialize briefly in order to reproduce.
[src:trousers/amazons] They were portrayed in a number of ancient epic poems and legends, such as the Labours of Heracles, the *Argonautica* and the *Iliad*.
[src:trousers/amazons] Courageous and fiercely independent, the Amazons, commanded by their queen, regularly undertook extensive military expeditions into the far corners of the world, from Scythia to Thrace, Asia Minor, and the Aegean Islands, reaching as far as Arabia and Egypt.
[src:trousers/amazons] Besides military raids, the Amazons are also associated with the foundation of temples and the establishment of numerous ancient cities like Ephesos, Cyme, Smyrna, Sinope, Myrina, Magnesia, Pygela, etc.
[src:trousers/amazons] The texts of the original myths envisioned the homeland of the Amazons at the periphery of the then-known world.
[src:trousers/amazons] Various claims to the exact place ranged from provinces in Asia Minor (Lycia, Caria, etc.) to the steppes around the Black Sea.
[src:trousers/amazons] However, authors most frequently referred to Pontus in northern Anatolia, on the southern shores of the Black Sea, as the independent Amazon kingdom where the Amazon queen resided at her capital Themiscyra, on the banks of the Thermodon river.
[src:trousers/amazons] Decades of archaeological discoveries of burial sites of female warriors, including royalty, in the Eurasian Steppes suggest that the horse cultures of the Scythian and Sarmatian peoples likely inspired the Amazon myth.
[src:trousers/amazons] In 2019, a grave with multiple generations of female Scythian warriors, armed and in golden headdresses, was found near Voronezh in southwestern Russia.
[src:trousers/amazons] In 2017, another discovery was made in Armenia, where the grave of a woman buried with jewelry dating back to the Iron Age reflected injuries and musculature of a horse-back warrior who frequented battle.
[src:trousers/amazons] A further explanation proposes Iranian **ama-janah* 'virility-killing' as source.
[src:trousers/amazons] There is no indication of such a practice in ancient works of art, in which the Amazons are always represented with both breasts, although one is frequently covered.
[src:trousers/amazons] According to Philostratus, Amazon babies were not fed just with the right breast.
[src:trousers/amazons] Author Adrienne Mayor suggests that the false etymology led to the myth.
[src:trousers/amazons] Herodotus used the terms *Androktones* (Ἀνδροκτόνες) 'killers/slayers of men' or 'of husbands', and *Androleteirai* (Ἀνδρολέτειραι) 'destroyers of men, murderesses'.
[src:trousers/amazons] Amazons are called *Antianeirai* (Ἀντιάνειραι) 'equivalent to men' and Aeschylus used the term *Styganor* (Στυγάνωρ) 'those who loathe all men'.
[src:trousers/amazons] In his work *Prometheus Bound* and in *The Suppliants*, Aeschylus referred to the Amazons as 'the unwed, flesh-devouring Amazons' (...τὰς ἀνάνδρους κρεοβόρους τ᾽ Ἀμαζόνας).
[src:trousers/amazons] In the *Hippolytus* tragedy, Phaedra calls Hippolytus, 'the son of the horse-loving Amazon' (...τῆς φιλίππου παῖς Ἀμαζόνος βοᾷ Ἱππόλυτος...).
[src:trousers/amazons] In his *Dionysiaca*, Nonnus calls the Amazons of Dionysus *Androphonus* (Ἀνδροφόνους) 'men slaying'.
[src:trousers/amazons] Herodotus stated that in the Scythian language, the Amazons were called *Oiorpata*, which he explained as being from *oior* 'man' and *pata* 'to slay'.
[src:trousers/amazons] The ancient Greeks never had any doubts that the Amazons were, or had been, real.
[src:trousers/amazons] Not the only people enchanted by warlike women of nomadic cultures, such exciting tales also come from ancient Egypt, Persia, India, and China.
[src:trousers/amazons] Greek heroes of old had encounters with the queens of their martial society and fought them.
[src:trousers/amazons] However, their original home was not exactly known, thought to be in the obscure lands beyond the civilized world.
[src:trousers/amazons] As a result, many classical scholars consider Amazons to be entirely fictional figures, invented by Greek men to serve as "anti-women" or to symbolize Persians.
[src:trousers/amazons] Some authors preferred comparisons to cultures of Asia Minor or even Minoan Crete.
[src:trousers/amazons] The most obvious historical candidates are Scythia (and more narrowly Sarmatia) in the Pontic–Caspian Steppe, and Lycia in Anatolia, in line with the accounts by Herodotus.
[src:trousers/amazons] In his *Histories* (5th century BCE), Herodotus claimed that the *Sauromatae* (predecessors of the Sarmatians), who ruled the lands between the Caspian Sea and the Black Sea, arose from a union of Scythians and Amazons.
[src:trousers/amazons] Herodotus also observed rather unusual customs among the Lycians of southwest Asia Minor.
[src:trousers/amazons] The Lycians followed matrilineal rules of descent, virtue, and status; they named themselves along their maternal family line and a child's status was determined by the mother's reputation.
[src:trousers/amazons] This remarkably high esteem of women and legal regulations based on maternal lines, still in effect in the 5th century BCE in the Lycian regions that Herodotus traveled to, suggested to him the idea that these people were descendants of the Amazons.
[src:trousers/amazons] Modern historiography no longer relies exclusively on textual and artistic material, but also on the vast archaeological evidence of over a thousand nomad graves from steppe territories, from the Black Sea all the way to Mongolia.
[src:trousers/amazons] Discoveries of battle-scarred female skeletons buried with their weapons (bows and arrows, quivers, and spears) prove that women warriors were not merely figments of imagination, but the product of the horse-centered warrior lifestyle of Scytho-Sarmatians.
[src:trousers/amazons] However, it is not known for certain whether these people were the inspiration for the Amazons of Greek mythology.
[src:trousers/amazons] According to myth, Otrera, the first Amazon queen, is the offspring of a romance between Ares the god of war and the nymph Harmonia of the Akmonian Wood, and as such a demigoddess.
[src:trousers/amazons] Early records refer to two events in which Amazons appeared prior to the Trojan War (before 1250 BCE).
[src:trousers/amazons] Within the epic context, Bellerophon, Greek hero, and grandfather of the brothers and Trojan War veterans *Glaukos and Sarpedon*, faced Amazons during his stay in Lycia, when King Iobates sent Bellerophon to fight the Amazons, hoping they would kill him, yet Bellerophon slew them all.
[src:trousers/amazons] The youthful King Priam of Troy fought on the side of the Phrygians, who were attacked by Amazons at the Sangarios River.
[src:trousers/amazons] There are Amazon characters in Homer's Trojan War epic poem, the *Iliad*, one of the oldest surviving texts in Europe (around 8th century BCE).
[src:trousers/amazons] The now lost epic *Aethiopis* (probably by Arctinus of Miletus, 6th century BCE), like the *Iliad* and several other epics, is one of the works that in combination form the Trojan War Epic Cycle.
[src:trousers/amazons] In one of the few references to the text, an Amazon force under queen Penthesilea, who was of Thracian birth, came to join the ranks of the Trojans after Hector's death and initially put the Greeks under serious pressure.
[src:trousers/amazons] Only after the greatest effort and the help of the reinvigorated hero Achilles, the Greeks eventually triumphed.
[src:trousers/amazons] Penthesilea died fighting the mighty Achilles in single combat.
[src:trousers/amazons] Homer himself deemed the Amazon myths to be common knowledge all over Greece, which suggests that they had already been known for some time before him.
[src:trousers/amazons] He was also convinced that the Amazons lived not at its fringes, but somewhere in or around Lycia in Asia Minor - a place well within the Greek world.
[src:trousers/amazons] Troy is mentioned in the *Iliad* as the place of Myrine's death.
[src:trousers/amazons] Later identified as an Amazon queen, according to Diodorus (1st century BCE), the Amazons under her rule invaded the territories of the Atlantians, defeated the army of the Atlantian city of Cerne, and razed the city to the ground.
[src:trousers/amazons] The Poet Bacchylides (6th century BCE) and the historian Herodotus (5th century BCE) located the Amazon homeland in *Pontus* at the southern shores of the Black Sea, and the capital Themiscyra at the banks of the Thermodon (modern Terme river), by the modern city of Terme.
[src:trousers/amazons] Herodotus also explains how it came to be that some Amazons would eventually be living in Scythia.
[src:trousers/amazons] A Greek fleet, sailing home upon defeating the Amazons in battle at the Thermodon river, included three ships crowded with Amazon prisoners.
[src:trousers/amazons] Once out at sea, the Amazon prisoners overwhelmed and killed the small crews of the prisoner ships and, despite not having even basic navigation skills, managed to escape and safely disembark at the Scythian shore.
[src:trousers/amazons] As soon as the Amazons had caught enough horses, they easily asserted themselves in the steppe in between the Caspian Sea and the Black Sea and, according to Herodotus, would eventually assimilate with the Scythians, whose descendants were the Sauromatae, the predecessors of the Sarmatians.
[src:trousers/amazons] Strabo (1st century BCE) visits and confirms the original homeland of the Amazons on the plains by the Thermodon river.
[src:trousers/amazons] However, long gone and not seen again during his lifetime, the Amazons had allegedly retreated into the mountains.
[src:trousers/amazons] Strabo, however, added that other authors, among them Metrodorus of Scepsis and Hypsicrates claim that after abandoning Themiscyra, the Amazons had chosen to resettle beyond the borders of the Gargareans, an all-male tribe native to the northern foothills of the Caucasian Mountains.
[src:trousers/amazons] The Amazons and Gargareans had for many generations met in secrecy once a year during two months in spring, in order to produce children.
[src:trousers/amazons] These encounters would take place in accordance with ancient tribal customs and collective offers of sacrifices.
[src:trousers/amazons] All females were retained by the Amazons themselves, and males were returned to the Gargareans.
[src:trousers/amazons] 5th century BCE poet Magnes sings of the bravery of the Lydians in a cavalry-battle against the Amazons.
[src:trousers/amazons] Hippolyte was an Amazon queen killed by Heracles, who had set out to obtain the queen's magic belt in a task he was to accomplish as one of the Labours of Heracles.
[src:trousers/amazons] Although neither side had intended to resort to lethal combat, a misunderstanding led to the fight.
[src:trousers/amazons] In the course of this, Heracles killed the queen and several other Amazons.
[src:trousers/amazons] In awe of the strong hero, the Amazons eventually handed the belt to Heracles.
[src:trousers/amazons] In another version, Heracles does not kill the queen, but exchanges her kidnapped sister Melanippe for the belt.
[src:trousers/amazons] Queen Hippolyte was abducted by Theseus, who took her to Athens, where they got married and had a son, Hippolytus.
[src:trousers/amazons] In other versions, the kidnapped Amazon is called Antiope, the sister of Hippolyte.
[src:trousers/amazons] In revenge, the Amazons invaded Greece, plundered some cities along the coast of Attica, and besieged and occupied Athens.
[src:trousers/amazons] Hippolyte, who fought on the side of Athens, according to another account was killed during the final battle along with all of the Amazons.
[src:trousers/amazons] According to Plutarch, the god Dionysus and his companions fought Amazons at Ephesus.
[src:trousers/amazons] The Amazons fled to Samos and Dionysus pursued them and killed a great number of them at a site since called *Panaema* (blood-soaked field).
[src:trousers/amazons] The Christian author Eusebius writes that during the reign of Oxyntes, one of the mythical kings of Athens, the Amazons burned down the temple at Ephesus.
[src:trousers/amazons] In another myth Dionysus unites with the Amazons to fight against Cronus and the Titans.
[src:trousers/amazons] Polyaenus writes that after Dionysus has subdued the Indians, he allies with them and the Amazons and takes them into his service, who serve him in his campaign against the Bactrians.
[src:trousers/amazons] Nonnus in his *Dionysiaca* reports about the Amazons of Dionysus, but states that they do not come from Thermodon.
[src:trousers/amazons] Amazons are also mentioned by historians and biographers of Alexander the Great who reports Queen Thalestris's seeking him out in order to bear him a child.
[src:trousers/amazons] However, other biographers of Alexander, including Plutarch, dispute the claim.
[src:trousers/amazons] He noted a moment when Alexander's naval commander Onesicritus read an Amazon myth passage of his *Alexander History* to King Lysimachus of Thrace who had taken part in the original expedition.
[src:trousers/amazons] A story in the *Alexander Romance* involves his conquest of the Amazons, carried out mainly by an exchange of threatening letters.
[src:trousers/amazons] Virgil's characterization of the Volsci warrior maiden Camilla in the *Aeneid* borrows from the myths of the Amazons.
[src:trousers/amazons] Philostratus, in *Heroica*, writes that the Mysian women fought on horses alongside the men, just as the Amazons.
[src:trousers/amazons] The Amazons are also said to have undertaken an expedition against the Island of Leuke, at the mouth of the Danube, where the ashes of Achilles were deposited by Thetis.
[src:trousers/amazons] The ghost of the dead hero so terrified the horses, that they threw off and trampled upon the invaders, who were forced to retreat.
[src:trousers/amazons] Virgil touches on the Amazons and their queen Penthesilea in his epic Aeneid (around 20 BCE).
[src:trousers/amazons] The biographer Suetonius had Julius Caesar remark in his *De vita Caesarum* that the Amazons *once ruled a large part of Asia*.
[src:trousers/amazons] Appian provides a vivid description of Themiscyra and its fortifications in his account of Lucius Licinius Lucullus's *Siege of Themiscyra* in 71 BCE during the Third Mithridatic War.
[src:trousers/amazons] An Amazon myth has been partly preserved in two badly fragmented versions around historical people in 7th century BCE Egypt.
[src:trousers/amazons] The Egyptian prince *Petechonsis* and allied Assyrian troops undertook a joint campaign into the *Land of Women*, to the *Middle East* at the border to India.
[src:trousers/amazons] *Petechonsis* initially fought the Amazons, but soon fell in love with their queen *Sarpot* and eventually allied with her against an invading Indian army.
[src:trousers/amazons] This story is said to have originated in Egypt independently of Greek influences.
[src:trousers/amazons] Sources provide names of individual Amazons, that are referred to as queens of their people, even as the head of a dynasty.
[src:trousers/amazons] Without a male companion, they are portrayed in command of their female warriors.
[src:trousers/amazons] Diodorus Siculus lists twelve Amazons who challenged and died fighting Heracles during his quest for Hippolyta's girdle: Aella, Philippis, Prothoe, Eriboea, Celaeno, Eurybia, Phoebe, Deianeira, Asteria, Marpe, Tecmessa, and Alcippe.
[src:trousers/amazons] After Alcippe's death, a group attack followed.
[src:trousers/amazons] Diodorus also mentions Melanippe, whom Heracles set free after accepting her girdle and Antiope as ransom.
[src:trousers/amazons] Diodorus lists another group with Myrina as the queen who commanded the Amazons in a military expedition in Libya, as well as her sister Mytilene, after whom she named the city of the same name.
[src:trousers/amazons] Myrina also named three more cities after the Amazons who held the most important commands under her, Cyme, Pitane, and Priene.
[src:trousers/amazons] Both Justin in his *Epitome of Trogus Pompeius* and Paulus Orosius give an account of the Amazons, citing the same names.
[src:trousers/amazons] Queens Marpesia and Lampedo shared the power during an incursion in Europe and Asia, where they were slain.
[src:trousers/amazons] Marpesia's daughter Orithyia succeeded them and was greatly admired for her skill on war.
[src:trousers/amazons] She shared power with her sister Antiope, but she was engaged in war abroad when Heracles attacked.
[src:trousers/amazons] Two of Antiope's sisters were taken prisoner, Melanippe by Heracles and Hippolyta by Theseus.
[src:trousers/amazons] Heracles latter restored Melanippe to her sister after receiving the queen's arms in exchange, though, on other accounts she was killed by Telamon.
[src:trousers/amazons] They also mention Penthesilea's role in the Trojan War.
[src:trousers/amazons] Another list of Amazons' names is found in Hyginus's *Fabulae*.
[src:trousers/amazons] Along with Hippolyta, Otrera, Antiope and Penthesilea, it attests the following names: Ocyale, Dioxippe, Iphinome, Xanthe, Hippothoe, Laomache, Glauce, Agave, Theseis, Clymene, Polydora.
[src:trousers/amazons] Perhaps the most important is Queen Otrera, consort of Ares and mother by him of Hippolyta and Penthesilea.
[src:trousers/amazons] She is also known for building a temple to Artemis at Ephesus.
[src:trousers/amazons] Another different set of names is found in Valerius Flaccus's *Argonautica*.
[src:trousers/amazons] He mentions Euryale, Harpe, Lyce, Menippe and Thoe.
[src:trousers/amazons] Of these Lyce also appears on a fragment, preserved in the *Latin Anthology* where she is said to have killed the hero Clonus of Moesia, son of Doryclus, with her javelin.
[src:trousers/amazons] Palaephatus, who himself might have been a fictional character, attempted to rationalize the Greek myths in his work *On Unbelievable Tales*.
[src:trousers/amazons] He suspected that the Amazons were probably men who were mistaken for women by their enemies because they wore clothing that reached their feet, tied up their hair in headbands, and shaved their beards.
[src:trousers/amazons] Probably the first in a long line of skeptics, he rejected any real basis for them, reasoning that because they did not exist during his time, most probably they did not exist in the past either.
[src:trousers/amazons] Stephanus of Byzantium (7th-century CE) provides numerous alternative lists of the Amazons, including for those who died in combat against Heracles, describing them as the "most prominent of their people".
[src:trousers/amazons] Both Stephanus and Eustathius connect these Amazons with the placename "Thibais", which they claim to have been derived from the Amazon Thiba's name.
[src:trousers/amazons] Several of Stephanus's Amazons served as eponyms for cities in Asia Minor, like Cyme and Smyrna or Amastris, who was believed to lend her name to the city previously known as Kromna, although in fact it was named after the historical Amastris.
[src:trousers/amazons] The city Anaea in Caria was named after an Amazon.
[src:trousers/amazons] In his work *Getica* (on the origin and history of the Goths, c.
[src:trousers/amazons] 551 CE), Jordanes asserts that the Goths' ancestors, descendants of Magog, originally lived in Scythia, at the Sea of Azov between the Dnieper and Don Rivers.
[src:trousers/amazons] When the Goths were abroad campaigning against Pharaoh Vesosis, their women, on their own successfully fended off a raid by a neighboring tribe.
[src:trousers/amazons] Emboldened, the women established their own army under Marpesia, crossed the Don and invaded eastward into Asia.
[src:trousers/amazons] Marpesia's sister Lampedo remained in Europe to guard the homeland.
[src:trousers/amazons] These women conquered Armenia, Syria, and all of Asia Minor, even reaching Ionia and Aeolis, holding this vast territory for 100 years.
[src:trousers/amazons] John Tzetzes lists in *Posthomerica* twenty Amazons, who fell at Troy.
[src:trousers/amazons] This list is unique in its attestation for all the names but Antianeira, Andromache, and Hippothoe.
[src:trousers/amazons] Other than these three, the remaining 17 Amazons were named as Toxophone, Toxoanassa, Gortyessa, Iodoce, Pharetre, Andro, Ioxeia, Oistrophe, Androdaixa, Aspidocharme, Enchesimargos, Cnemis, Thorece, Chalcaor, Eurylophe, Hecate, and Anchimache.
[src:trousers/amazons] Medieval and Renaissance authors credit the Amazons with the invention of the battle-axe.
[src:trousers/amazons] This is probably related to the *sagaris*, an axe-like weapon associated with both Amazons and Scythian tribes by Greek authors (see also Thracian tomb of Aleksandrovo kurgan).
[src:trousers/amazons] Paulus Hector Mair expresses astonishment that such a "manly weapon" should have been invented by a "tribe of women", but he accepts the attribution out of respect for his authority, Johannes Aventinus.
[src:trousers/amazons] The Amazons and Queen Hippolyta are also referenced in Geoffrey Chaucer's *Canterbury Tales* in "The Knight's Tale".
[src:trousers/amazons] Amazons continued to be subject of scholarly debate during the European Renaissance, and with the onset of the Age of Exploration, encounters were reported from ever more distant lands.
[src:trousers/amazons] In 1542, Francisco de Orellana reached the Amazon River, naming it after the *Icamiabas*, a tribe of warlike women he claimed to have encountered and fought on the Nhamundá River, a tributary of the Amazon.
[src:trousers/amazons] Afterwards the whole basin and region of the Amazon (*Amazônia* in Portuguese, *Amazonía* in Spanish) were named after the river.
[src:trousers/amazons] Amazons also figure in the accounts of both Christopher Columbus and Walter Raleigh.
[src:trousers/amazons] Beginning around 550 BCE. depictions of Amazons as daring fighters and equestrian warriors appeared on vases.
[src:trousers/amazons] After the Battle of Marathon in 490 BCE the *Amazon battle - Amazonomachy* became popular motifs on pottery.
[src:trousers/amazons] By the sixth century BCE, public and privately displayed artwork used the Amazon imagery for pediment reliefs, sarcophagi, mosaics, pottery, jewelry and even monumental sculptures, that adorned important buildings like the Parthenon in Athens.
[src:trousers/amazons] Amazon motifs remained popular until the Roman imperial period and into Late antiquity.
[src:trousers/amazons] Apart from the artistic desire to express the passionate womanhood of the Amazons in contrast with the manhood of their enemies, some modern historians interpret the popularity of Amazon in art as indicators of societal trends, both positive and negative.
[src:trousers/amazons] Greek and Roman societies, however, utilized the Amazon mythology as a literary and artistic vehicle to unite against a commonly held enemy.
[src:trousers/amazons] The metaphysical characteristics of Amazons were seen as personifications of both nature and religion.
[src:trousers/amazons] Roman authors like Virgil, Strabo, Pliny the Elder, Curtius, Plutarch, Arrian, and Pausanias advocated the greatness of the state, as Amazon myths served to discuss the creation of origin and identity for the Roman people.
[src:trousers/amazons] Amazons in Roman literature and art have many faces, such as the *Trojan ally, the warrior goddess, the native Latin, the warmongering Celt, the proud Sarmatian, the hedonistic and passionate Thracian warrior queen, the subdued Asian city, and the worthy Roman foe*.
[src:trousers/amazons] In Renaissance Europe, artists started to reevaluate and depict Amazons based on Christian ethics.
[src:trousers/amazons] Queen Elizabeth of England was associated with Amazon warrior qualities (*the foremost ancient examples of feminism*) during her reign and was indeed depicted as such.
[src:trousers/amazons] Though, as explained in *Divina Virago* by Winfried Schleiner, Celeste T.
[src:trousers/amazons] Wright has given a detailed account of the bad reputation Amazons had in the Renaissance.
[src:trousers/amazons] She notes that she has not found any Elizabethans comparing the Queen to an Amazon and suggests that they might have hesitated to do so because of the association of Amazons with enfranchisement of women, which was considered contemptible.
[src:trousers/amazons] Elizabeth was present at a tournament celebrating the marriage of the Earl of Warwick and Anne Russell at Westminster Palace on November 11, 1565, involving male riders dressed as Amazons.
[src:trousers/amazons] They accompanied the challengers carrying their heraldry.
[src:trousers/amazons] These riders wore crimson gowns, masks with long hair attached, and swords.
[src:trousers/amazons] Peter Paul Rubens and Jan Brueghel depicted the Battle of the Amazons around 1598, a *most dramatic baroque painting*, followed by a painting of the Rococo period by Johann Georg Platzer, also titled *Battle of the Amazons*.
[src:trousers/amazons] In 19th-century European Romanticism German artist Anselm Feuerbach occupied himself with the Amazons as well.
[src:trousers/amazons] The medieval Borgia Velletri map pictures females with bow and arrow and others with spear and shield, with thedescription "The land formerly of illustrious women", at the north (on the bottom) of *Edilus fluuius maximus* (the Volga river).
[src:trousers/amazons] In the medieval Fra Mauro map, a land called Ancient Greek: Ἀμαζόnia, romanized: *Amazonia* is placed on the Middle Volga region.
[src:trousers/amazons] Speculation that the idea of Amazons, specifically the Amazons known to the Greeks, contains a core of reality is based on archaeological discoveries at kurgan burial sites in the steppes of southern Ukraine and Russia.
[src:trousers/amazons] Armed women accounted for up to 25% of Sarmatian military burials.
[src:trousers/amazons] Russian archaeologist Vera Kovalevskaya asserts that when Scythian men were abroad fighting or hunting, women would have to be able to competently defend themselves, their animals, and their pastures.
[src:trousers/amazons] A 2024 report in *The Observer* described Bronze Age graves in Nakhchivan, Azerbaijan, where women were found buried with weapons including arrowheads, a bronze dagger, and a mace, presenting the finds as part of a broader pattern of female warrior burials in the Caucasus and Eurasian steppe.
[src:trousers/amazons] In early 20th century Minoan archeology, a theory regarding Amazon origins in Minoan civilization was raised in an essay by Lewis Richard Farnell and John Myres.
[src:trousers/amazons] According to Myres, the tradition interpreted in the light of evidence furnished by supposed Amazon cults seems to have been very similar and may have even originated in Minoan culture.
[src:trousers/amazons] The city of Samsun in modern-day Samsun Province, Turkey features an *Amazon Village* museum, to help bring attention to the legacy of the Amazons and to promote both academic interest and tourism.
[src:trousers/amazons] The Amazon warriors have been seen as a symbol of empowerment for feminist movements.
[src:trousers/amazons] The legacy has empowered and encouraged other women to build their strength and stand against societal norms.
[src:trousers/amazons] They have inspired countless amounts of women to stand up for themselves and what they believe.
[src:trousers/amazons] An annual *Amazon Celebration Festival* takes place in the Terme district.
[src:trousers/amazons] During the Ottoman–Egyptian invasion of Mani in 1826, in the battle of Diros, the women of Mani defeated the Ottoman army and for this were given the name of 'The Amazons of Diros'.
[src:trousers/amazons] From 1936 to 1939, annual propaganda events, called Night of the Amazons (*Nacht der Amazonen*) were performed in Nazi Germany at the Nymphenburg Palace Park in Munich.
[src:trousers/amazons] At one such open-air event, announced as evening highlights of the International Horse Racing Week of Munich-Riem, bare-breasted variety show girls, the SS Cavalry, and international guests performed, with 2,500 total participants.
[src:trousers/amazons] These revues served to promote an allegedly emancipated female role and a cosmopolitan and foreigner-friendly Nazi regime.
[src:trousers/amazons] The Neptune trojans, asteroids 60° ahead or beyond Neptune on its orbit, are individually named after mythological Amazons.
[src:trousers/american-english] Varieties of American English include many patterns of pronunciation, vocabulary, grammar, and particularly spelling that are unified nationwide but distinct from other forms of English around the world.
[src:trousers/american-english] However, historical and present linguistic evidence does not support the notion of there being one single mainstream American accent.
[src:trousers/american-english] The sound of American English continues to evolve, with some local accents disappearing, but several larger regional accents having emerged in the 20th century.
[src:trousers/american-english] The use of English in the United States is a result of British colonization of the Americas.
[src:trousers/american-english] The first wave of English-speaking settlers arrived in North America during the early 17th century, followed by further migrations in the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:trousers/american-english] English thus predominated in the colonies even by the end of the 17th century's first immigration of non-English speakers from Western Europe and Africa.
[src:trousers/american-english] Firsthand descriptions of a fairly uniform American English (particularly in contrast to the diverse regional dialects of British English) became common after the mid-18th century, while at the same time speakers' identification with this new variety increased.
[src:trousers/american-english] Since the 18th century, American English has developed into some new varieties, including regional dialects that retain minor influences from waves of immigrant speakers of diverse languages, primarily European languages.
[src:trousers/american-english] Some racial and regional variation in American English reflects these groups' patterns of geographic settlement, segregation, and resettlement.
[src:trousers/american-english] This can be seen, for example, in the influence of 18th-century Protestant Ulster Scots immigrants (known in the U.S. as the Scotch-Irish) in Appalachia developing Appalachian English and the 20th-century Great Migration bringing African-American Vernacular English to the Great Lakes urban centers.
[src:trousers/american-english] Most American English accents fall under an umbrella known as General American.
[src:trousers/american-english] Rather than one particular accent, General American is a spectrum of those American accents that Americans themselves do not associate with some particular region, ethnicity, or socioeconomic group.
[src:trousers/american-english] General American features are used most by Americans in formal contexts or who are highly educated.
[src:trousers/american-english] Regional accents whose native features are perceived as General American include the accents of the North Midland (parts of the Midwest), Western New England, and the West.
[src:trousers/american-english] The General American sound system's scope of influence and degree of expansion has been debated by linguists since the term was first used roughly a century ago.
[src:trousers/american-english] Many late-20th and early-21st century studies are showing that it is gradually ousting the regional accents in urban areas of the South and the interior North, New York City, Philadelphia, and many other areas.
[src:trousers/american-english] It can generally be said that younger Americans are avoiding their traditional local features in favor of this more nationwide norm.
[src:trousers/american-english] Furthermore, even General American itself appears to be evolving, with linguists identifying new features in speakers born since the last quarter of the 20th century, like a merger of the low-back vowels and a potentially related vowel shift, that are spreading across the nation.
[src:trousers/american-english] Like many British accents, T glottalization is the norm in American accents, though only in particular environments (with *satin* pronounced [ˈsæʔn̩], not [ˈsætn̩]).
[src:trousers/american-english] Specifically, the LOT–PALM merger is complete among most Americans and the LOT–THOUGHT merger among roughly half.
[src:trousers/american-english] A three-way LOT–PALM–THOUGHT merger is also very common, meaning that words like *baht*, *bot*, and *bought* are all homophones.
[src:trousers/american-english] Most Americans pronounce the diphthong /aɪ/ before a voiceless consonant different from that same vowel before a voiced consonant: thus, in *price* and *bright* versus in *prize* and *bride*.
[src:trousers/american-english] For many, outside the South, the first element of the diphthong is a higher and shorter vowel sound when in pre-voiceless position as opposed to pre-voiced position.
[src:trousers/american-english] All of these phenomena are explained in further detail under General American.
[src:trousers/american-english] Unlike American accents, the traditional standard accent of (southern) England has evolved a *trap–bath* split.
[src:trousers/american-english] Moreover, American accents preserve /h/ at the start of syllables, while perhaps a majority of the regional dialects of England participate in /h/ dropping, particularly in informal contexts.
[src:trousers/american-english] The process of developing new lexical items began as soon as British English-speaking colonists in North America began borrowing names for unfamiliar flora, fauna, and topography from the Native American languages.
[src:trousers/american-english] Examples of such names are *opossum, raccoon, squash*, *moose* (from Algonquian), *wigwam*, and *moccasin*.
[src:trousers/american-english] American English speakers have integrated traditionally non-English terms and expressions into the mainstream cultural lexicon; for instance, *en masse*, from French; *cookie*, from Dutch; *kindergarten* from German, and *rodeo* from Spanish.
[src:trousers/american-english] Landscape features are often loanwords from French or Spanish, and the word *corn*, used in England to refer to wheat (or any cereal), came to denote the maize plant, the most important crop in the U.S.
[src:trousers/american-english] Other common differences between UK and American English include: *aerial* (UK) vs.
[src:trousers/american-english] *apartment*, *fringe* (UK; for hair hanging over the forehead) vs.
[src:trousers/american-english] Most Mexican Spanish contributions came after the War of 1812, with the opening of the West, like *ranch* (now a common house style).
[src:trousers/american-english] Due to Mexican culinary influence, many Spanish words are incorporated in general use when talking about certain popular dishes: cilantro (instead of coriander), queso, tacos, quesadillas, enchiladas, tostadas, fajitas, burritos, and guacamole.
[src:trousers/american-english] These words usually lack an English equivalent and are found in popular restaurants.
[src:trousers/american-english] New forms of dwelling created new terms *(lot, waterfront)* and types of homes like *log cabin, adobe* in the 18th century; *apartment, shanty* in the 19th century; *project, condominium, townhouse, mobile home* in the 20th century; and parts thereof *(driveway, breezeway, backyard)*.
[src:trousers/american-english] Already existing English words—such as *store, shop, lumber*—underwent shifts in meaning; others remained in the U.S. while changing in Britain.
[src:trousers/american-english] Science, urbanization, and democracy have been important factors in bringing about changes in the written and spoken language of the United States.
[src:trousers/american-english] From the world of business and finance came new terms (*merger, downsize, bottom line*), from sports and gambling terminology came, specific jargon aside, common everyday American idioms, including many idioms related to baseball.
[src:trousers/american-english] The names of some American inventions remained largely confined to North America (*elevator* [except in the aeronautical sense], *gasoline*) as did certain automotive terms (*truck*, *trunk*).
[src:trousers/american-english] New foreign loanwords came with 19th and early 20th century European immigration to the U.S.; notably, from Yiddish *(chutzpah, schmooze, bupkis, glitch*) and German (*hamburger, wiener*).
[src:trousers/american-english] American English has always shown a marked tendency to use words in different parts of speech and nouns are often used as verbs.
[src:trousers/american-english] Examples of nouns that are now also verbs are *interview, advocate, vacuum, lobby, pressure, rear-end, transition, feature, profile, hashtag, head, divorce, loan, estimate, X-ray, spearhead, skyrocket, showcase, bad-mouth, vacation, major,* and many others.
[src:trousers/american-english] Compounds coined in the U.S. are for instance *foothill, landslide* (in all senses), *backdrop, teenager,* *brainstorm, bandwagon, hitchhike, smalltime,* and a huge number of others.
[src:trousers/american-english] Other compound words have been founded based on industrialization and the wave of the automobile: five-passenger car, four-door sedan, two-door sedan, and station-wagon (called an estate car in British English).
[src:trousers/american-english] Some are euphemistic *(human resources, affirmative action, correctional facility).* Many compound nouns have the verb-and-preposition combination: *stopover, lineup, tryout, spin-off, shootout, holdup, hideout, comeback, makeover,* and many more.
[src:trousers/american-english] Some prepositional and phrasal verbs are in fact of American origin (*win out, hold up, back up/off/down/out, face up to* and many others).
[src:trousers/american-english] Noun endings such as *-ee (retiree), -ery (bakery), -ster (gangster)* and *-cian (beautician)* are also particularly productive in the U.S.
[src:trousers/american-english] A number of words and meanings that originated in Middle English or Early Modern English and that have been in everyday use in the United States have since disappeared in most varieties of British English; some of these have cognates in Lowland Scots.
[src:trousers/american-english] Terms such as *fall* ("autumn"), *faucet* ("tap"), *diaper* ("nappy"; itself unused in the U.S.), *candy* ("sweets"), *skillet*, *eyeglasses*, and *obligate* are often regarded as Americanisms.
[src:trousers/american-english] *Fall*, however, came to denote the season in 16th century England, a contraction of Middle English expressions like "fall of the leaf" and "fall of the year".
[src:trousers/american-english] *Gotten* (past participle of *get*) is often considered to be largely an Americanism.
[src:trousers/american-english] Other words and meanings were brought back to Britain from the U.S., especially in the second half of the 20th century; these include *hire* ("to employ"), *I guess* (famously criticized by H.
[src:trousers/american-english] Fowler), *baggage*, *hit* (a place), and the adverbs *overly* and *presently* ("currently").
[src:trousers/american-english] Some of these, for example, *monkey wrench* and *wastebasket*, originated in 19th century Britain.
[src:trousers/american-english] The adjectives *mad* meaning "angry", *smart* meaning "intelligent", and *sick* meaning "ill" are also more frequent in American (and Irish) English than British English.
[src:trousers/american-english] Linguist Bert Vaux created a survey, completed in 2003, polling English speakers across the United States about their specific everyday word choices, hoping to identify regionalisms.
[src:trousers/american-english] American English and British English (BrE) differ in relatively minor ways in their grammar and writing conventions.
[src:trousers/american-english] The first large American dictionary, *An American Dictionary of the English Language*, known as Webster's Dictionary, was written by Noah Webster in 1828, codifying several of these spellings.
[src:trousers/american-english] Often, these differences are a matter of relative preferences rather than absolute rules; and most are not stable since the two varieties are constantly influencing each other, and American English is not a standardized set of dialects.
[src:trousers/american-english] Differences in orthography are also minor.
[src:trousers/american-english] The main differences are that American English usually uses spellings such as *flavor* for British *flavour*, *fiber* for *fibre*, *defense* for *defence*, *analyze* for *analyse*, *license* for *licence*, *catalog* for *catalogue* and *traveling* for *travelling*.
[src:trousers/american-english] Noah Webster popularized such spellings in America, but he did not invent most of them.
[src:trousers/american-english] AmE almost always uses *-ize* in words like *realize*.
[src:trousers/american-english] BrE prefers *-ise*, but also uses *-ize* on occasion (see: Oxford spelling).
[src:trousers/american-english] There are a few differences in punctuation rules.
[src:trousers/american-english] British English is more tolerant of run-on sentences, called "comma splices" in American English, and American English prefers that periods and commas be placed inside closing quotation marks even in cases in which British rules would place them outside.
[src:trousers/american-english] American English also favors the double quotation mark ("like this") over the single ('as here').
[src:trousers/american-english] AmE sometimes favors words that are morphologically more complex, whereas BrE uses clipped forms, such as AmE *transportation* and BrE *transport* or where the British form is a back-formation, such as AmE *burglarize* and BrE *burgle* (from *burglar*).
[src:trousers/american-english] However, while individuals usually use one or the other, both forms will be widely understood and mostly used alongside each other within the two systems.
[src:trousers/american-english] as well as the related Telsur Project's regional maps.
[src:trousers/american-english] Any region may also contain speakers of a "General American" accent that resists the marked features of their region.
[src:trousers/american-english] The regional sounds of present-day American English are reportedly engaged in a complex phenomenon of "both convergence and divergence": some accents are homogenizing and leveling, while others are diversifying and deviating further away from one another.
[src:trousers/american-english] As of the 20th century, the middle and eastern Great Lakes area, Chicago being the largest city with these speakers, also ushered in certain unique features, including the fronting of the LOT /ɑ/ vowel in the mouth toward [a] and tensing of the TRAP /æ/ vowel wholesale to [eə].
[src:trousers/american-english] These sound changes have triggered a series of other vowel shifts in the same region, known by linguists as the "Inland North".
[src:trousers/american-english] The Inland North shares with the Eastern New England dialect (including Boston accents) a backer tongue positioning of the GOOSE /u/ vowel (to [u]) and the MOUTH /aʊ/ vowel (to [ɑʊ~äʊ]) in comparison to the rest of the country.
[src:trousers/american-english] Ranging from northern New England across the Great Lakes to Minnesota, another Northern regional marker is the variable fronting of /ɑ/ before /r/, for example, appearing four times in the stereotypical Boston shibboleth *Park the car in Harvard Yard*.
[src:trousers/american-english] Several other phenomena serve to distinguish regional American accents.
[src:trousers/american-english] Boston, Pittsburgh, Upper Midwestern, and Western U.S. accents have fully completed a merger of the LOT vowel with the THOUGHT vowel (/ɑ/ and /ɔ/, respectively): a *cot–caught* merger, which is rapidly spreading throughout the whole country.
[src:trousers/american-english] However, the South, Inland North, and a Northeastern coastal corridor passing through Rhode Island, New York City, Philadelphia, and Baltimore typically preserve an older *cot–caught* distinction.
[src:trousers/american-english] For that Northeastern corridor, the realization of the THOUGHT vowel is particularly marked, as depicted in humorous spellings, like in *tawk* and *cawfee* (*talk* and *coffee*), which intend to represent it being tense and diphthongal: [oə].
[src:trousers/american-english] A split of TRAP into two separate phonemes, using different *a* pronunciations for example in *gap* [æ] versus *gas* [eə], further defines New York City as well as Philadelphia–Baltimore accents.
[src:trousers/american-english] Most Americans preserve all historical /r/ sounds, using what is known as a rhotic accent.
[src:trousers/american-english] Non-rhoticity makes a word like *car* sound like *cah* or *source* like *sauce*.
[src:trousers/american-english] New York City and Southern accents are the most widely recognized regional accents in the country, as well as the most stigmatized and socially disfavored.
